1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 {The Queen’s Gambit Declined enjoys lasting popularity
with players of all levels. Its basic plans are straightforward and easy to
understand: develop the kingside with ...Nf6, ...Be7, and ...0-0 - then go for
active play, often based on the move ...c5. It has a sound and solid
reputation and an aspect appealing to players of different styles lies in the
opportunity to choose between various lines against all of White's main tries.
In Queen's Gambit Declined - Part 1, we build a complete repertoire for Black
after 3.Nf3 and 3.Nc3, except for the Catalan, which will be the focus of Part
2.} 3. Nf3 (3. Nc3 Nf6 4. cxd5 {The ever-popular Exchange Variation is
analysed in Lessons 16 - 18. Rare alternatives to 4.Bg5 and 4.cxd5 are dealt
with in Lesson 14.} ({Lesson 15 is dedicated to the "old" main line of the QGD
} 4. Bg5 {. We concentrate on the comparatively uncommon but interesting} dxc4
$5) 4... exd5 5. Bg5 c6 6. e3 h6 7. Bh4 Be7 8. Bd3 O-O 9. Nge2 {, the
repertoire is based on the fresh continuation} Ne8 $5 {, transferring the
knight to the optimal d6-square.}) 3... Nf6 4. Nc3 {For rare alternatives on
move four - see Lesson 1.} (4. e3 {- see Lesson 2.}) (4. Bg5 {- see Lesson 3.})
(4. g3 {leads to the Catalan, which will be analysed in Queen's Gambit
Declined - Part 2.}) 4... Be7 {Now White' main moves are 5.Bg5 and 5.Bf4.} 5.
Bf4 {This is currently White's most popular move in this position. For lesser
options on move five - see Lesson 4.} (5. Bg5 h6 6. Bh4 ({The exchange on f6} 
6. Bxf6 Bxf6 {is the theme of Lesson 8.}) 6... O-O 7. e3 {For White's lesser
alternatives on move seven - see Lesson 9.} Nbd7 {Black has good alternatives
in the Tartakower and the Lasker Defence, but in this course we trust in the
fire-proof 7...Nbd7 (Lesson 10).}) (5. cxd5 {- see Lesson 5.}) (5. e3 {- see
Lesson 6.}) (5. g3 {- see Lesson 7.}) 5... O-O 6. e3 {A survey of the
alternatives to 6.e3 is found in Lesson 11.} {In this course we will meet 5.
Bf4 with} b6 {- see Lessons 12 & 13.} *

