1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 {We start our theoretical journey by studying all the
lines with 3.Nf3 and turn to 3.Nc3 beginning with Lesson 14.} Nf6 {In this
lesson, we will analyse rare lines. 4.Nc3 is the main move, which we will
study starting with Lesson 4. The moves 4.e3 and 4.Bg5 will be dealt with in
Lesson 2 and 3.} 4. Bf4 (4. Qc2 {White supports c4 with the queen and plans to
continue with Bf4 or Bg5.} dxc4 $5 {Now, White must either lose time with his
queen or sacrifice the c4-pawn.} ({Other fully playable moves are} 4... Be7) ({
and} 4... c5 {, leading to a good version (for Black) of the Tarrasch Defence.}
) 5. Qxc4 (5. e4 $6 {Sacrificing the pawn with this or 5.Nbd2 seems to offer
insufficient compensation.} b5 6. a4 Bb7 {This counterattack against e4 is the
most active way of playing.} (6... c6) 7. axb5 (7. e5 Bxf3 8. exf6 Bb7 9. fxg7
Bxg7 10. axb5 Qxd4 11. Bxc4 Nd7 $15) 7... Bxe4 8. Qxc4 Bxf3 9. gxf3 Bd6 10. f4
Nbd7 11. Bg2 Rb8 12. Nc3 O-O $15 {Black has excellent chances due to White's
numerous weaknesses.}) (5. Nbd2 b5 (5... c5 $5) 6. a4 c6 7. b3 cxb3 8. Nxb3 Be7
9. e4 O-O 10. Bd2 Na6 $15 {Black already has some advantage. For example} 11.
axb5 cxb5 12. Bxb5 Nb4 $17 {, and White is in some trouble.}) (5. e3 c5 ({
Black is also fine after} 5... b5 6. a4 c6 7. axb5 cxb5 8. b3 Na6 9. bxc4 Nb4
10. Qb3 bxc4 11. Bxc4 Bd6 12. O-O O-O 13. Bd2 a5 14. Nc3 Bb7 $11) 6. Bxc4 {
We have a position from the Queen's Gambit Accepted where White has spent a
tempo on Qc2.} cxd4 (6... a6) 7. exd4 (7. Nxd4 Bd7 {[%cal Gb8c6]}) 7... Nc6 8.
O-O Nxd4 {Taking the pawn may seem risky, but I think that Black is doing fine:
} (8... Be7 9. Rd1) 9. Nxd4 Qxd4 10. Bb5+ (10. Rd1 Qe5) (10. Be3 Qe5) 10... Bd7
11. Be3 Qb4 12. Bxd7+ Nxd7 13. a3 Qa5 14. Nc3 Be7 15. Rfd1 Qa6 $132 {[%cal
Gd7f6,Ge8g8] White's compensation is about to evaporate after ...Nf6, ...0-0.})
5... a6 6. Bf4 (6. g3 b5 {[%cal Gc8b7] Black will continue with ...Bb7, ...
Nbd7, and ...c5 with very good play.}) (6. Bg5 b5 7. Bxf6 gxf6 8. Qc3 Nd7 9. e3
Bb7 $132 {[%cal Gc7c5] White managed to spoil Black's pawn structure, but this
is more than compensated for by Black's pair of bishops.}) 6... Bd6 $1 7. Bxd6
(7. Bg3 b5 8. Qc2 Bb7 9. Nbd2 Nbd7 10. e3 O-O 11. Bd3 h6 12. O-O Rc8 $11 {
[%cal Gc7c5] ...c5 is coming, with a good game for Black.}) 7... cxd6 ({
We should avoid} 7... Qxd6 $6 8. Nbd2 $14 {[%cal Ge2e4]}) 8. e3 b5 9. Qb3 Bb7
$11 {Black has a good position; his bishop is nicely placed on b7.}) (4. g3 {
leads to the Catalan and will be analysed in Queen's Gambit Declined - Part 2.}
) 4... dxc4 {Since White cannot play e4 and 5.e3 can be met with 5...b5, White
has to lose some time to regain the c4-pawn.} ({Also good are} 4... c5) ({and} 
4... Bb4+) 5. Qa4+ (5. e3 $6 b5 $15) (5. Nc3 c6 6. a4 ({After} 6. e4 $6 {
Black safely defends the pawn with} b5 $15) 6... Bb4 7. g3 O-O 8. Bg2 a5 9. O-O
Nd5 10. Bd2 Be7 11. e4 (11. Ne5 Nb6) 11... Nb4 $132 {Black has good chances in
this Catalan-style position.}) 5... Nbd7 6. e3 (6. Qxc4 $6 c5 7. e3 a6 $15 {
[%cal Gb7b5]}) 6... Nd5 {This is Black's most ambitious move - threatening ...
Nb6 and...Nxf4.} ({Other options are} 6... c5 7. Bxc4 cxd4 8. Nxd4 Be7) ({or} 
6... a6 7. Bxc4 Be7) 7. Bxc4 (7. Qxc4 $6 Bb4+ 8. Nbd2 Bxd2+ 9. Nxd2 Nxf4 10.
exf4 Nb6 11. Qc5 Bd7 $15 {[%cal Gd7c6] leads to a positional advantage for
Black.}) 7... Nxf4 (7... Bb4+ {is sufficient for equality.} 8. Nc3 Bxc3+ 9.
bxc3 Nxf4 ({Black must avoid} 9... Nxc3 $2 {when} 10. Qa5 $16 {regains the
pawn with a big advantage.}) 10. exf4 c5 11. O-O O-O 12. Rfd1 Qc7 $11) 8. exf4
Bd6 9. g3 O-O 10. Be2 {White defends against ...Nb6.} (10. Qc2 b6 {[%cal Gc8b7]
is similar.}) 10... a6 (10... c5 $5) 11. O-O b5 12. Qc2 Bb7 $11 {Black has an
easy game.} *

