1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. e3 {We will look at the analogous continuation
4.Nc3 Be7 5.e3 in Lesson 6.} Be7 {We will concentrate on this simple
developing move which is in the spirit of the Queen's Gambit Declined.} ({
Of course, Black has other decent moves, such as:} 4... b6) (4... a6) (4... c5)
5. b3 (5. Nbd2 O-O 6. b3 (6. Bd3 {is well met with} c5 7. dxc5 (7. cxd5 $6 cxd4
8. exd4 (8. Nxd4 Qxd5 $15) 8... Qxd5 9. O-O Nc6 $15) 7... Na6 $1 8. O-O Nxc5 9.
Be2 {Black has won a useful tempo and is more than fine after} b6 $11 {[%cal
Gc8b7]}) 6... c5 (6... b6 7. Bb2 Bb7 {is another good option.}) 7. Bd3 (7. dxc5
Nbd7 {[%cal Gd7c5]}) (7. Bb2 cxd4 8. exd4 b6 9. Bd3 Bb7 {transposes to the
main lines.}) 7... cxd4 8. exd4 b6 9. Bb2 Bb7 {also leads to the main lines.
White and Black can reach this position by many different move orders.}) (5.
Bd3 dxc4 {After the bishop has moved, it's very logical to take on c4.} 6. Bxc4
{Black has reached a position from the Queen's Gambit Accepted with the
valuable extra tempo ...Be7.} a6 ({Similar are:} 6... c5) ({and} 6... O-O) 7.
O-O (7. a4 {Once White plays a4 to prevent ...b5, Black can always use the
b4-square.} c5 8. O-O Nc6 9. dxc5 Bxc5 10. Nbd2 (10. Qxd8+ Kxd8 $11 {[%csl Gb4]
[%cal Gd8e7]}) 10... Qe7 11. b3 b6 12. Bb2 Bb7 13. Qe2 O-O $11 {The pawn
structure is symmetrical and all of Black's pieces are well-placed.}) 7... O-O
(7... b5 {is a slightly worse move order because after} 8. Bd3 Bb7 {White has}
9. a4 $14) 8. Qe2 b5 9. Bd3 Nbd7 10. Rd1 (10. e4 $6 c5 $15 {Black is already
better - if e5, there's always ...Nd5.}) (10. a4 bxa4 11. Rxa4 c5 $132 {
[%cal Gc8b7]}) 10... Bb7 $11 {[%cal Gc7c5,Gd8b8] Black will soon push ...c5}) (
5. cxd5 exd5 6. Bd3 O-O 7. O-O Re8 8. Nc3 Bd6 {The typical plan - the bishop
is excellent on d6 and Black will continue with ...c6, ...Nbd7-Nf8, or ...Bg4,
Nbd7.} 9. Qc2 (9. Nb5 Bf8 {[%cal Gc7c6]}) 9... c6 (9... Na6 $5 10. a3 c6) (9...
Bg4 $5) 10. b3 Qe7 (10... Nbd7 {[%cal Gd7f8]}) 11. Bb2 Bg4 12. Ne5 Bh5 {
We should not take on e5 since it would open the diagonal of the b2-bishop.}
13. f4 (13. e4 dxe4 14. Nxe4 Nxe4 15. Bxe4 Bg6 $11) 13... Nbd7 14. e4 (14. Rae1
$6 Bg6 $15) 14... dxe4 15. Nxe4 Nxe4 16. Bxe4 Bg6 {The following complications
are not unfavourable for Black:} 17. f5 Bh5 18. Rae1 Nxe5 19. dxe5 Bxe5 20. f6
gxf6 21. Bxh7+ Kg7 22. Bxe5 fxe5 23. Re3 Bg6 24. Bxg6 fxg6 25. Rg3 Qe6 $11 {
White's compensation for the pawn is sufficient for equality at best.}) (5. Be2
dxc4 {is similar to 5.Bd3.}) (5. Nc3 {transposes to Lesson 6.}) 5... O-O 6. Bb2
(6. Bd3 c5 {is very similar to the main line.}) 6... c5 (6... b6 {is another
possible plan.}) 7. Nbd2 (7. cxd5 cxd4 ({Another option is} 7... Nxd5 8. dxc5
Na6) 8. Nxd4 ({After} 8. Qxd4 exd5 {[%cal Gb8c6] Black will gain a useful
tempo with ...Nc6.}) (8. dxe6 Bb4+ $1 9. Nbd2 Bxe6 10. exd4 {Black gets
excellent compensation for the sacrificed pawn.} (10. Bxd4 $6 Nc6) 10... Bxd2+
11. Qxd2 (11. Nxd2 $6 Bd5 {[%csl Gd5] is already very tricky to handle for
White.} 12. f3 (12. Nc4 Re8+ 13. Ne3 Qd6 $1 14. Be2 Rxe3 $1 15. fxe3 Bxg2 16.
Bf3 ({White lands in a very dangerous situation after} 16. Rg1 $6 Qxh2 17. Qc2
Nc6 18. O-O-O Nb4 19. Qd2 Be4 $17) 16... Bxh1 17. Bxh1 Nc6 $15 {[%csl Re1]
[%cal Gd6h2,Ga8e8] The material is equal, but White's king is still in the
centre.}) 12... Ng4 $1 {White was about to consolidate with Kf2, so Black
should play energetically.} 13. fxg4 Qh4+ 14. Ke2 (14. g3 $6 {loses material
after} Qe7+ 15. Qe2 Qxe2+ 16. Bxe2 Bxh1 $17) 14... Nc6 (14... Re8+ 15. Kd3 Nc6)
15. Bc3 Rfe8+ (15... Qg5 $5) 16. Kd3 Rac8 {White has to defend with
engine-like precision to survive.} 17. Rc1 b5 $1 18. Kc2 b4 19. Ba1 Nxd4+ 20.
Kb2 Qf6 21. Kb1 Qg6+ 22. Kb2 Qf6 (22... Nc2 23. Nc4 Na3 24. Nxa3 bxa3+ 25. Kxa3
Qd6+ 26. Kb2 Qf6+ $11) 23. Kb1 Qg6+ $11) 11... Ne4 ({White also has some
problems to solve after} 11... Re8 $5 12. Be2 Ne4 13. Qf4 Qa5+ 14. Kf1 Bd5 15.
Ne5 Nc6 $40) 12. Qe3 Qa5+ 13. Kd1 (13. Nd2 $2 Re8 14. f3 (14. O-O-O Nf6 $19)
14... Bf5 15. Kd1 Nf6 $17) 13... Nf6 14. Qd2 Qb6 $40 {Black has a clear
initiative; with the king in the centre, White's position is difficult to
handle.}) 8... Qxd5 {This is the simplest.} ({Black is ok in the forced line
after} 8... Bb4+ 9. Nd2 Ne4 10. N4f3 Qxd5 11. a3 Bxd2+ 12. Nxd2 Nxd2 13. Qxd2
Qxb3 14. Qd4 f6 15. Bc4 Qb6 16. Qxb6 axb6 17. Rd1 Kf7 $11) 9. Nc3 Qa5 10. a3
Rd8 $11 {[%cal Gb8c6,Ge6e5]}) (7. dxc5 {is harmless.} dxc4 8. Qxd8 Rxd8 9. Bxc4
Ne4 $11) (7. Bd3 cxd4 8. exd4 b6 9. O-O Bb7 10. Nc3 Nbd7 {I prefer this
flexible move over the more popular 10...Nc6, which is also fine.} (10... Nc6
11. Re1 Rc8 {is played in the majority of games.}) 11. Re1 (11. Qe2 Qc7 {
Black connects the rooks and also has ...Qf4 in some lines.} 12. Rfd1 (12. Rac1
dxc4 13. bxc4 Qf4 14. Ne5 Rad8 $132) (12. Ne5 dxc4 13. Bxc4 Nxe5 {The most
straightforward way to equalise.} (13... a6 {is also sufficient.} 14. Rac1 b5
15. Nd5 Qd8 16. Nxe7+ Qxe7 17. Bd3 Rac8 $11) 14. dxe5 Qc6 15. f3 Qc5+ 16. Kh1
Nd5 $11) 12... Rfd8 13. h3 (13. Rac1 Qf4 14. g3 Qg4 $11) 13... Rac8 $11) 11...
a6 {Not the only move, but it's useful in general.} 12. Rc1 Re8 13. Qe2 dxc4 (
13... Nf8 $5) 14. bxc4 Rc8 15. Nd2 (15. Ne5 Nxe5 16. dxe5 Nd7 17. Be4 Qc7 $11)
15... Nf8 16. Nde4 Qd7 $11 {[%cal Gf8g6] In my opinion the position is easier
to play with Black - he is solid and has the more complact pawn structure.}) (
7. Nc3 cxd4 8. exd4 b6 9. Bd3 Bb7 {transposes to 7.Bd3.}) 7... cxd4 8. exd4 (8.
Nxd4 e5 $5 {The most direct way.} (8... Nc6 {also looks fine.} 9. Nxc6 bxc6 10.
Bd3 Bd6 {[%cal Ge6e5]} 11. O-O e5 12. Rc1 Qe7 $11) 9. N4f3 d4 10. exd4 ({
White must avoid} 10. Nxe5 $2 dxe3 11. fxe3 Re8 $17) 10... exd4 (10... e4 $6
11. Ne5) 11. Bd3 {Taking on d4 is too risky:} (11. Nxd4 $2 Bc5 $19) (11. Bxd4
$2 Nc6 12. Bb2 Re8 13. Be2 Bg4 14. O-O Bb4 15. h3 Bh5 $19) 11... Nc6 12. O-O
Bg4 13. h3 (13. a3 a5) 13... Bh5 14. Ne4 (14. a3 a5 15. Qc2 Bc5 $11) 14... Ne5
15. Be2 Nxf3+ 16. Bxf3 Nxe4 17. Bxh5 d3 {White has the pair of bishops but the
pawn on d3 offers sufficient counterchances.} 18. Bf3 (18. Qg4 $6 Bf6) 18... f5
19. Bxe4 fxe4 20. Qg4 Bf6 21. Bxf6 Qxf6 22. Qxe4 (22. Rae1 {is similar.} d2 23.
Rxe4 Rad8 24. Qe2 Qb2 25. Rd1 Qxa2 26. Re7 Qc2 $11) 22... Rad8 {Even though
White managed to win a pawn, the mightly d3-passer provides obvious
compensation.} 23. Qxb7 Qd4 24. Rad1 d2 {[%csl Gd2]} 25. Qb5 h6 $44) 8... b6 9.
Bd3 Bb7 10. O-O Nbd7 {Again, I prefer this over the more popular 10...Nc6.} (
10... Nc6 $5) 11. Qe2 {The other moves are not changing much.} (11. Re1 Rc8) (
11. Rc1 Rc8) 11... Rc8 12. Rac1 (12. Rad1 Qc7 13. Rfe1 Rfd8 $11) (12. Rfe1 Qc7
13. Rac1 Qb8 $11) 12... Rc7 $5 {After this, Black's queen can go to b8 or a8.}
({Another decent plan is} 12... Re8 {[%cal Gd7f8] , followed by transferring
the knight to g6.}) 13. Rfd1 (13. Ne5 dxc4 14. bxc4 Nxe5 15. Qxe5 (15. dxe5 $6
{White is worse after} Nh5 $1 16. Bxh7+ Kxh7 17. Qxh5+ Kg8 18. Rfd1 Qe8 $15 {
Black is down a pawn, but he has the pair of bishops and White has some
weaknesses.}) 15... Qd6 $132) (13. Rfe1 Re8 $11) 13... Qb8 (13... Qa8 {is also
possible.}) 14. Nf1 Rd8 15. Ne3 Rcc8 $11 {We have a double-edged position with
good counterchances for Black.} *

