1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. Bg5 {After 4.Nc3, apart from 4...Be7, there
are a number of possible lines Black can choose from (4...dxc4, 4...c5, 4...
Bb4). So, White sometimes starts with 4.Bg5 to limit Black's options.} dxc4 $5
{Alternatively, we could play 4...Be7, but I want to show this interesting
extra option.} (4... Be7 {will probably transpose to the lines after 4.Nc3 Be7
5.Bg5.}) 5. e4 {The most principled reply.} (5. Qa4+ {White makes sure that he
regains the pawn, but loses some time with his queen in the process.} Nbd7 6.
e3 (6. e4 Be7 7. Nc3 h6 8. Bxf6 (8. Bf4 a6 9. Qxc4 c5 10. dxc5 Bxc5 11. e5 Nd5
$1 12. Nxd5 exd5 13. Qc3 ({White cannot take the pawn with} 13. Qxd5 $2 {
since he loses material after} Qa5+ $1 14. Ke2 (14. Bd2 Bxf2+ $19) (14. Kd1
Qa4+) (14. Qd2 Bb4 $19) 14... Qb5+ $1) 13... Qb6 14. Be3 O-O $132 {Only Black
can be better here.}) 8... Bxf6 9. Bxc4 O-O 10. e5 (10. O-O $6 {runs into} Bxd4
$1 {, winning a pawn.} 11. Nxd4 Nb6 12. Nc6 Qd6 $17) 10... Be7 11. Be2 c5 12.
O-O Nb6 13. Qc2 Bd7 $132 {The bishop comes to c6 - Black is doing very well.})
(6. Nc3 c5 (6... a6 {is also good.}) 7. e3 Qb6 8. O-O-O {Now Black can force
an equal endgame with} Qb4 9. Bxc4 Qxa4 10. Nxa4 Ne4 11. Bh4 Be7 12. Bxe7 Kxe7
$11) (6. Qxc4 a6 {[%cal Gb7b5,Gc8b7]}) 6... Be7 7. Bxc4 (7. Qxc4 O-O 8. Be2 a6
9. O-O (9. a4 {fails to prevent} b5 $1 10. axb5 $4 axb5 $19 {[%cal Gb5c4,Ga8a1]
}) 9... b5 10. Qc2 Bb7 11. a4 c5 12. axb5 axb5 13. Rxa8 Qxa8 14. Bxf6 Nxf6 15.
dxc5 b4 {Black will eventually regain the pawn with equal chances. For example}
16. Qc4 Rb8 17. Qxb4 (17. Nbd2 Nd7 18. Nb3 Bd5 $11) 17... Bxf3 18. Bxf3 Rxb4
19. Bxa8 Bxc5 $11) 7... h6 8. Bxf6 (8. Bh4 {is the same story as in the
previous lines.} a6 9. O-O O-O 10. Be2 b5 11. Qc2 Bb7 12. a4 c5 $11) 8... Bxf6
9. O-O O-O $11 {[%cal Gc7c5,Ge6e5]}) (5. Nc3 a6 $1 6. a4 (6. e4 b5 {Black is
about to consolidate the pawn with ...Bb7, etc., so White must go for forcing
play.} 7. e5 (7. a4 Bb7 8. axb5 axb5 9. Rxa8 Bxa8 10. e5 h6 11. Bd2 Nd5 12.
Nxb5 Nb6 $132 {[%csl Ga8][%cal Gf8e7,Ge8g8] Black has a good position.}) 7...
h6 8. Bh4 g5 9. Nxg5 hxg5 10. Bxg5 Nbd7 11. exf6 {Compared to the Botvinnik
Variation of the Semi-Slav, Black has played ...a6 instead of ...c6, which is
in his favour.} Bb7 {[%csl Gb7][%cal Gb7g2]} 12. Be2 (12. d5 Nc5 13. dxe6 Nxe6
14. Qxd8+ Rxd8 $15) (12. h4 Nxf6 13. d5 Bh6 $132) 12... Bh6 (12... Bxg2 $6 13.
Rg1 Bb7 14. Bf3 $36) 13. Bxh6 Rxh6 14. Bf3 Bxf3 15. Qxf3 Rxf6 16. Qe4 Nb6 17.
O-O b4 18. Nd1 Qd6 $132 {Black has good chances - ...Rf4 is threatened and he
can play either ...Ke7 or ...0-0-0 to activate the queen's rook.}) 6... Nc6 {
I like this continuation, making use of the squares weakened by 6.a4.} (6... c5
{also looks good.}) 7. e3 Na5 $1 {With the inclusion of the moves ...a6 and a4,
the knight is placed excellently on a5.} 8. Nd2 (8. Ne5 Bb4 9. Be2 ({White is
worse after} 9. Nxc4 Qd5 $15 {[%cal Ga5c4,Gd5g5]}) 9... c5 $132) (8. Be2 c5
$132) 8... c5 9. dxc5 ({Black isn't any worse in the endgame after} 9. Nxc4
cxd4 10. Qxd4 Qxd4 11. exd4 Nxc4 12. Bxc4 Bb4 13. O-O O-O 14. Rfd1 Bd7 $11)
9... Bxc5 10. Bxc4 Bd7 11. O-O Be7 $11 {[%cal Ge8g8,Ga8c8]}) ({After} 5. Nbd2
$6 {Black can play} b5 6. a4 c6 $15 {, when Nbd2 does not combine well with
sacrificing a pawn.}) 5... c5 {I prefer this over the sharp 5...b5.} (5... b5
$5 {is a double-edged alternative, leading to a theoretical line after} 6. a4
c6 7. Nc3 Qb6 $13) 6. Nc3 ({White ends up worse after} 6. e5 $6 h6 $15) (6.
Bxc4 cxd4 7. O-O Nc6 {White has some compensation for the sacrificed pawn, but
Black has entirely sufficient chances either.} 8. Nbd2 {The most logical
continuation - White wants to play e5-Ne4.} (8. e5 {is insufficient due to} h6
9. Bc1 (9. Bh4 $6 g5 10. Bg3 Ne4 11. Bb5 Bd7 $17) 9... Nd7 10. Re1 (10. Bb5 Qb6
) 10... a6 $15 {White cannot easily regain the pawn, ½-½ (59) Andreikin,D 
(2729)-Dominguez Perez,L (2739) Chess.com INT 2023.}) (8. Bb5 {is also not
sufficient.} Bd7 9. Bxc6 Bxc6 10. Nxd4 Bxe4 11. Nc3 Bc6 $15) 8... h6 9. Bh4 Be7
10. e5 Nd7 $1 {Increasing the pressure against e5.} (10... Nd5 {allows} 11.
Bxe7 Qxe7 12. Ne4) 11. Bxe7 (11. Bg3 O-O 12. Rc1 a5 13. Nb3 (13. Qe2 Nc5 $132)
13... Qb6 14. Nbxd4 Rd8 15. Nxc6 bxc6 16. Qe2 Bb7 $11 {[%cal Gc6c5] Black has
good counter chances in this double-edged position.}) 11... Qxe7 12. Qe2 (12.
Re1 O-O 13. Nb3 Rd8 $132 {Black has good chances; White struggles to regain
the pawn, 1-0 (49) Deac,B (2679)-Yuan,Q (2373) Chess.com INT 2022.}) 12... O-O
13. Nb3 Nb6 14. Bd3 Nb4 15. Bb1 {White must try to keep the bishop in order to
retain some attacking chances. However, after} d3 16. Qe4 Rd8 17. Ne1 g6 18.
Nxd3 Nxd3 19. Bxd3 Rd5 20. Be2 Qc7 21. f4 Bd7 $11 {[%cal Gd7c6] Black is
completely OK.}) 6... cxd4 7. Qxd4 (7. Nxd4 Bc5 8. Nf3 ({Black has the
advantage after} 8. Qa4+ $6 Bd7 9. Qxc4 Qb6 10. Bxf6 gxf6 11. O-O-O O-O 12. Kb1
Rc8 $15 {due to the pair of bishops.}) 8... h6 $5 (8... Qxd1+ {is a reliable
alternative.} 9. Rxd1 h6) 9. Qxd8+ Kxd8 {Black's king will be well-placed on
