1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. Nc3 {With this lesson, we begin analysing the
lines after 4.Nc3, which together with 4.g3 (the Catalan - see Part 2) are the
main moves.} Be7 5. Qc2 {In Lesson 4, we see various rare options on move five.
5.cxd5, 5.e3, 5.g3, and the main continuations 5.Bg5 and 5.Bf4 will be
examined in the following lessons.} (5. g4 {This comes somewhat prematurely,
yet it's playable. It can be interesting for its surprise effect, though Black
has different ways of reaching a good position.} O-O (5... dxc4 $5 {is another
decent option. It's logical to open the centre in reaction to an attack on the
wing.} 6. g5 {leads to an unclear position after} (6. e4 Bb4 7. Bxc4 Nxe4 8.
O-O Nf6 {We have reached a position from the Vienna Variation, except that
White's pawn is on g4...} 9. g5 Nd5 10. Qb3 Nxc3 11. bxc3 (11. Qxb4 $6 Nd5)
11... Bd6 12. Bd3 Nd7 13. Re1 O-O 14. Qc2 g6 {Now, Black can go for the
positional pawn sacrifice} 15. h4 b5 $1 16. Bxb5 Bb7 17. Nd2 c5 $132 {, with
active counterplay.}) 6... Nd5 7. e4 Nxc3 8. bxc3 b5 9. a4 b4 10. Bxc4 O-O $132
) 6. g5 Ne4 {Black is doing fine in general, though the arising positions are
rather complicated.} 7. Qd3 (7. h4 c5 {It's crucial to generate counterplay by
striking in the centre.} 8. Bg2 cxd4 9. Nxe4 (9. Nxd4 Nxc3 10. bxc3 dxc4 $15)
9... dxe4 10. Nxd4 f5 11. gxf6 Bb4+ 12. Kf1 (12. Bd2 $6 Qxf6 $17 {[%cal Gf6f2]}
) 12... Qxf6 13. Be3 Bc5 14. b4 Bxb4 {The complications after} 15. Qb3 (15.
Bxe4 Rd8 $15) 15... Bd2 {lead to equality. For example} 16. Rd1 Bxe3 17. Qxe3
Rd8 18. Bxe4 Nc6 19. Bxc6 bxc6 20. Kg2 Ba6 21. Qxe6+ Qxe6 22. Nxe6 Rxd1 23.
Rxd1 Bxc4 $11) (7. Bg2 Nxc3 8. bxc3 Nd7 $132 {[%cal Gd7b6]}) 7... Nxc3 {
I prefer this over winning the g5-pawn.} (7... Nxg5 8. Nxg5 Bxg5 9. Bxg5 Qxg5
10. h4 Qd8 $13 {We have won a pawn, but White has some activity.}) 8. bxc3 (8.
Qxc3 $6 a5 9. Bd2 c5 10. dxc5 Nd7 $15) 8... dxc4 9. Qxc4 b6 10. Bg2 (10. h4 c5
11. h5 Ba6 12. Qa4 b5 13. Qc2 Nd7 14. Bg2 Bb7 15. h6 (15. g6 $6 cxd4 16. gxh7+
Kh8 17. cxd4 Rc8 18. Qd3 Bf6 $17) 15... g6 16. O-O Rc8 $132 {Black has good
counterplay, while his king is safe.}) 10... Bb7 11. h4 c5 12. O-O Nc6 $132 {
the position is about equal, with enough counterplay for Black, ½-½ (45)
Esipenko,A (2723)-Alekseenko,K (2698) Chess.com INT 2022.}) (5. Qb3 {is
somewhat weird, in my opinion. Black can react with an immediate} c5 ({Similar
is} 5... O-O 6. cxd5 exd5 7. Bg5 c5) 6. cxd5 (6. dxc5 $6 d4 7. Na4 Ne4 $15)
6... exd5 {Black has a good version of the Tarrasch Defence, in which White
has played a premature Qb3.} 7. dxc5 ({After} 7. Bg5 {Black wins a useful
tempo with} c4 8. Qc2 Nc6 $132) 7... O-O 8. Bg5 (8. Be3 Na6 9. g3 Nxc5 10. Qd1
Nce4 $11) 8... Be6 ({Sacrificing a pawn with} 8... Na6 $5 9. Bxf6 Bxf6 10. Nxd5
Qa5+ 11. Nd2 Be5 $44 {[%cal Ga6c5] is another good way to play.}) 9. Nd4 (9.
Qc2 Bxc5 10. e3 h6 11. Bh4 Nc6 $132 {[%cal Gd5d4]}) 9... Na6 {The most logical
move - ...Nxc5 is coming with tempo.} ({The other options are:} 9... h6) (9...
Bxc5) 10. c6 {This is the only critical try.} (10. e3 Nxc5 11. Qc2 Rc8 12. Bd3
Nfe4 13. Bxe7 Qxe7 $11) 10... bxc6 11. Nxc6 Qc7 {White has won a pawn, but he
