1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. Nc3 Be7 5. cxd5 {Of course, this is playable,
but in general, it leads to a favourable (for Black) version of the Exchange
Variation.} exd5 {Black will continue with ...c6 when White has no way to stop
...Bf5. Usually, the exchange of light-squared bishops (after a possible Bd3)
is to Black's benefit in the Carlsbad structure.} 6. Bg5 (6. Qc2 c6 {Now 7.Bg5
or 7.Bf4 will transpose to the main lines.}) (6. Bf4 c6 7. e3 (7. h3 {White
has the idea of meeting ...Bf5 with g4, but this is not too dangerous for
Black.} Bf5 8. e3 (8. Qb3 Qb6 {is similar to a later Qb3.}) (8. g4 Bg6 9. Ne5 (
9. Bg2 {seems passive and does not pose problems.} Nbd7 10. O-O h5 11. Ne5 (11.
g5 Ne4) 11... Nxe5 12. dxe5 Ne4 $132) (9. Qb3 Qb6 10. e3 Nbd7 11. Nh4 Qxb3 12.
axb3 Bc2 {leads to some complications that are not unfavourable for Black. For
example} 13. Nf5 (13. Kd2 Bxb3 14. Nf5 Bf8 $132) 13... Bxf5 14. gxf5 g6 15. Bd3
Nh5 $11 {Black has enough counterplay. White has the pair of bishops, but
Black's structure is superior.}) (9. e3 Qb6 10. Qb3 {transposes to 9.Qb3.})
9... Nbd7 10. Bg2 (10. Nxg6 hxg6 11. e3 Nf8 12. Qb3 Qb6 13. Be2 Ne6 14. Bg3
Qxb3 15. axb3 g5 $11 {Black's structure is extremely solid - White struggles
to find an active plan.}) 10... Nxe5 11. dxe5 Nd7 {We have a complex position
with good counterchances for Black.} 12. O-O h5 (12... f6 $5) 13. e4 hxg4 14.
hxg4 dxe4 15. Bxe4 (15. Nxe4 Bxe4 16. Bxe4 Nc5 $11) 15... Nc5 16. Bxg6 fxg6 $11
{[%cal Gc5e6,Ge8f7] After the exchange of queens, Black's knight will be
excellent on e6.}) 8... Qb6 {This is the most accurate move.} (8... Nbd7 9. g4
Bg6 10. Nh4 {is a better version for White compared to 8.g4.}) 9. Bd3 ({After} 
9. Qb3 {Black can prevent g4 once and for all with} h5 $11 {, also securing
the bishop's position on f5.}) (9. Qc1 Nbd7 10. g4 {Black has two acceptable
ways to meet this:} (10. Be2 h6 11. O-O O-O $11) 10... Be4 {is the most
straightforward.} (10... Bg6 $5 11. Nh4 Be4 12. Rg1 O-O) 11. Be2 (11. Nxe4 Nxe4
12. Bd3 h5 $132) 11... h6 12. Nxe4 Nxe4 $132) 9... Bxd3 ({We should avoid} 9...
Qxb2 $6 10. Bxf5 Qxc3+ 11. Kf1 Nbd7 12. g4 $14 {[%cal Ga1b1,Gf1g2] - White has
more than enough compensation for the exchange.}) 10. Qxd3 Nbd7 11. O-O ({
Black has the better chances after} 11. O-O-O $6 O-O 12. Nh4 g6 13. Nf3 Rfe8
14. h4 {1-0 (42) Erigaisi,A (2778)-Grischuk,A (2689) Chess.com INT 2024} Bb4 $1
15. Ne5 (15. h5 Bxc3 16. bxc3 Ne4 17. hxg6 fxg6 $17) 15... Nxe5 16. Bxe5 Bxc3
17. Qxc3 Ne4 18. Qe1 c5 $15) 11... O-O 12. Na4 (12. Rab1 a5 $11) 12... Qb4 13.
Qc2 a5 14. Rfc1 Rfe8 $11 {Black has zero problems here, 1-0 (86) Erigaisi,A 
