1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. Nc3 Be7 5. e3 {This is similar to 4.e3, which
was seen in Lesson 2. The difference is that White has committed himself to
Nc3, while Black's bishop is already on e7.} O-O 6. a3 {This is the modern way
to play this line. White makes a useful waiting move and will choose his next
move depending on Black's reply.} (6. Bd3 dxc4 $1 7. Bxc4 {Black has reached a
position from the Queen's Gambit Accepted with an extra tempo.} a6 {The most
flexible move.} (7... c5 8. O-O Nc6 {is also fully playable.}) 8. e4 {is the
only active try for White.} (8. O-O b5 9. Bd3 Bb7 10. e4 c5 11. dxc5 (11. e5
Nd5) 11... Nbd7 12. b4 a5 13. Ba3 axb4 14. Bxb4 Bxc5 $11) (8. a4 c5 9. O-O Nc6
$11 {We already have seen similar positions in the previous lessons. The
inclusion of ...a6 and a4 is in Black's favour since he can use the b4-square.}
) (8. Bd3 c5 $11) 8... c5 9. e5 (9. O-O $6 {is very good for Black after} cxd4
10. Nxd4 Qc7 $15) 9... Nfd7 $1 10. Bf4 (10. d5 $6 Nb6) 10... cxd4 (10... b5 {
is another decent option.} 11. Bd3 cxd4 12. Nxd4 Nc5 13. Bc2 Bb7 $132) 11. Nxd4
Qc7 12. Bd3 (12. Bxe6 {might look tempting, but does not work too well after}
fxe6 13. Nxe6 Qc4 $1 {[%cal Gc4e6,Gc4f4]} 14. Nxf8 Nxf8 15. Qd5+ Qxd5 16. Nxd5
Bd8 17. Be3 Be6 18. Rd1 Nc6 $15) 12... Nc5 ({I prefer to avoid} 12... Nxe5 13.
O-O $13 {White has ideas with Bxh7+, followed by Qh5.}) 13. O-O Rd8 14. Bb1 Nc6
15. Qc2 g6 16. Nxc6 bxc6 17. Rd1 Bb7 $132 {Black will eventually push ...c5.
White will lose some time regrouping the b1-bishop.}) (6. b3 c5 (6... b6 {
is another possible setup.}) 7. cxd5 ({After} 7. dxc5 dxc4 {is a simple
equaliser.} (7... Bxc5 8. Bb2 Nc6 $11) 8. Qxd8 Rxd8 9. Bxc4 Bxc5 10. O-O a6 11.
Bb2 b5 12. Be2 Bb7 $11 {1/2 (29) Kacheishvili,G (2607)-Hess,R (2595)/ICC INT
2012/The Week in Chess 935 (29)}) (7. Bb2 cxd4 8. Nxd4 (8. exd4 b6 9. Bd3 Bb7
10. O-O {was analysed in Lesson 2.}) 8... e5 $5 {An energetic move, playing
for the initiative.} (8... dxc4 {is an easy way to equalise.} 9. Bxc4 a6 10.
Be2 b5 11. Bf3 Ra7 12. O-O e5 13. Nde2 Bf5 $11) 9. Nf3 Be6 10. Nxe5 (10. cxd5
Nxd5) 10... Qc7 11. Nf3 dxc4 12. Bxc4 Bxc4 13. bxc4 Qxc4 14. Qe2 Rc8 $11) (7.
