1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. Nc3 Be7 5. Bg5 {In this lesson, we begin to
study the old main line of the Queen's Gambit Declined, the move 5.Bg5.} h6 {
The most accurate move order. After 5...0-0 6.e3 h6, Black's king is already
committed to the kingside, which gives White some extra attacking options.} 6.
Bxf6 {Here, we mainly deal 6.Bxf6 while the Lessons 9 & 10 are dedicated to
the lines after 6.Bh4.} (6. Bf4 {is rarely played. Compared to 5.Bf4, Black
has the extra tempo ...h6, which can be quite useful.} O-O (6... c5 {is
similar.}) 7. e3 c5 8. dxc5 Bxc5 9. Rc1 (9. Qc2 Nc6 10. a3 Qe7 $11) 9... Nc6
10. cxd5 exd5 11. Be2 d4 12. exd4 Nxd4 13. Nxd4 Qxd4 14. Qxd4 Bxd4 15. O-O Be6
$11) 6... Bxf6 7. e3 {This is the main continuation. White has a large number
of alternatives:} (7. g3 {Combining Bxf6 with Catalan-style play is not
promising. Black is fine after} O-O 8. Bg2 dxc4 9. O-O Nd7 $132 {, when he can
continue with either ...c5 or ...Nb6.}) ({After} 7. e4 dxe4 8. Nxe4 {Black
immediately attacks d4 with} Nc6 $1 {After} 9. Nxf6+ (9. d5 Ne5 $15) 9... Qxf6
