1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. Nc3 Be7 5. Bg5 h6 6. Bh4 {We can call this the
"old" main line of the Queen's Gambit Declined. After} O-O {White's main move
is 7.e3, which we will study in Lesson 10. Overall, these lines are no longer
considered dangerous for Black, but we should know what to do against them.} 7.
Rc1 (7. Qc2 c5 {This is the most straightforward continuation, although by no
means the only one.} (7... b6) (7... dxc4) 8. dxc5 (8. cxd5 cxd4 9. Nxd4 Nxd5
10. Bxe7 Qxe7 11. Nxd5 exd5 12. e3 Nc6 $1 $132) 8... Qa5 {I like this best;
again, there are several reasonable alternatives:} (8... Nc6) (8... dxc4) (8...
Na6) 9. cxd5 Nxd5 10. Bxe7 Nxe7 {Black has no problems getting an equal
position regardless of what White plays.} 11. e3 (11. g3 Qxc5 12. Bg2 Nbc6 13.
Rc1 e5 $11 {1/2 (49) Gelfand,B (2733)-Jakovenko,D (2753)/Odessa 2009/CBM 130
Extra (49)}) 11... Qxc5 12. Be2 Nbc6 (12... Nd5 13. Rc1 Nxc3 14. Qxc3 Qxc3+ 15.
Rxc3 Nc6) 13. Rc1 (13. O-O Nd5 14. Rfc1 Nxc3 15. Qxc3 Qxc3 16. Rxc3 Bd7 $11) (
13. a3 Nd5 14. Rc1 Nxc3 15. Qxc3 Qxc3+ 16. Rxc3 Bd7 $11) 13... Rd8 14. O-O Bd7
15. a3 (15. Rfd1 Be8) (15. Qb1 Be8) 15... Ne5 $11) (7. cxd5 Nxd5 {With 7...
exd5 we could transpose to the Exchange Variation, but 7...Nxd5 is simpler.} 8.
Bxe7 (8. Nxd5 Bxh4) 8... Qxe7 9. e3 (9. Nxd5 exd5 10. Rc1 c6 11. e3 Bf5 12. Bd3
Bxd3 13. Qxd3 Nd7 $11 {Black has no problems in this Carlsbad Structure -
White has exchanged too many pieces.}) (9. Qb3 c5 10. dxc5 (10. Nxd5 {is
similar.} exd5 11. dxc5 Nc6 $132) 10... Qxc5 11. Nxd5 exd5 12. e3 Nc6 $11 {
Black will soon push ...d4.}) (9. Qc2 Nb4 $5 10. Qb3 c5 $11) (9. Rc1 Nxc3 10.
Rxc3 {White has prevented ...c5, but Black can prepare ...e5.} Nc6 11. e3 e5
$11 12. d5 $6 Rd8) 9... Nxc3 10. bxc3 b6 11. Bd3 Bb7 12. O-O c5 $11 {Black
will continue with ...Nd7, ...Rfd8, ...Rac8, with comfortable equality.}) 7...
c5 $5 {As after 7.Qc2, Black is ready for this pawn push.} ({Alternatives are} 
7... b6) ({and} 7... dxc4) 8. cxd5 (8. dxc5 {leads to simplifications.} dxc4 9.
e3 Qxd1+ 10. Rxd1 Bxc5 11. Bxc4 Bb4 $11) (8. e3 {poses no problems.} cxd4 9.
Nxd4 Nc6 $11) 8... cxd4 9. Nxd4 (9. Qxd4 exd5 {[%cal Gb8c6]} 10. e3 Nc6 11. Qa4
Qb6 $11 {Black has enough counterplay to compensate the isolated pawn.}) 9...
Nxd5 10. Bxe7 Nxe7 11. e3 Nbc6 $11 {The game is completely level; for example}
12. Nxc6 Nxc6 13. Qxd8 Rxd8 {[%cal Gg8f8,Gf8e7,Gc8d7,Gd7e8,Ga8c8]} *

