1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. Nc3 Be7 5. Bf4 {This is probably White's best
continuation in this move order. It's also very popular and a lot of theory
has been accumulated. We begin by analysing White's alternatives to the main
move 6.e3.} O-O 6. a3 {White's idea is to play e4 after Black takes on c4.} (6.
Qc2 c5 $1 {This is a typical reaction in various lines with Qc2 in the Queen's
Gambit Declined.} 7. dxc5 {This is best. White runs the risk of becoming worse
with other moves.} (7. O-O-O $2 {is risky and objectively bad.} cxd4 (7... Na6
$5) 8. Nxd4 Nbd7 {8...Nc6 is fine, but this, threatening ...e5, is even
stronger.} (8... Nc6 9. Nxc6 bxc6 $15) 9. cxd5 e5 10. d6 (10. Nf5 Bb4 11. Bg5
Nc5 $17) 10... Bxd6 11. Nf5 exf4 12. Nxd6 Ng4 13. Nce4 Qb6 $17 {White lags
with his kingside development and f2 is attacked.}) (7. Rd1 $6 {is another
dubious move.} cxd4 8. Nxd4 Nc6 (8... Nbd7 $5 {[%cal Ge6e5]}) 9. Nxc6 bxc6 $15
{With the centre nicely protected by the c6-pawn, Black is doing great.}) (7.
e3 cxd4 8. Nxd4 (8. exd4 {leads to a good version of an IQP position.} dxc4 9.
Bxc4 Nc6 $132) 8... Nbd7 9. Bg3 Nb6 10. cxd5 Nbxd5 $132 {[%cal Ge7b4] Black
will continue with ...Bb4 - he is doing great.}) 7... Na6 {We regain the
c-pawn with the knight, while ...Nb4 can also be an option.} 8. Rd1 {The only
critical try.} (8. cxd5 Nb4 9. Qc1 Nbxd5 $132 {[%cal Gd8a5] Black will regain
the c5-pawn with a good game.}) (8. e3 Nxc5 9. Be2 (9. cxd5 Nxd5 10. Nxd5 {
Here we can take back with either the queen or the pawn.} exd5 {is the more
ambitious move.} (10... Qxd5 11. Be2 b6 12. O-O Bb7 13. Rfd1 Qe4 $11) 11. Be5 (
11. Be2 $6 Qa5+ $1 $17 12. Qd2 $2 Nd3+ $1 13. Bxd3 Bb4 $19) 11... Ne4 12. a3 (
12. Bd3 Qa5+ 13. Ke2 Bg4 $132 {looks unpleasant for White.}) 12... Bf5 13. Bd3
Rc8 14. Qd1 Bf6 15. Bxf6 Qxf6 16. Rb1 Rc5 17. O-O Bg4 18. Be2 Rfc8 $11 {
Black's activity offsets the Isolated Queen's Pawn.}) 9... dxc4 10. Bxc4 a6 {
[%cal Gb7b5]} 11. a4 Qa5 {After a4, Black's queen is well placed on a5 since
the b4-square is available.} 12. O-O b6 13. Ne5 Bb7 $11) (8. O-O-O $2 {is just
bad.} Qa5 $17) 8... Qa5 (8... Nxc5 9. cxd5 exd5 10. e3 Nce4 {is also possible.}
) 9. cxd5 ({After} 9. Bd6 Bxd6 10. cxd6 dxc4 11. e4 b5 12. e5 Nd7 $132 {
[%cal Gb5b4] White's central pawns are in danger.}) (9. a3 dxc4 $132) 9... Nb4
10. Qa4 (10. Qb1 {is harmless.} Nfxd5 11. Bd2 Nxc3 12. Bxc3 Qa4 13. b3 Qa3 $132
) 10... Qxa4 11. Nxa4 Ne4 $1 {[%cal Gb4c2] A nice resource - Black is
threatening mate in one.} 12. e3 Nxd5 13. Bc4 (13. Bd3 Nxc5 14. Nxc5 Bxc5 $11)
13... Nxf4 14. exf4 Nxc5 15. Nxc5 Bxc5 16. O-O b6 {The endgame is about equal.}
