1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 Nf6 4. Nc3 Be7 5. Bf4 O-O 6. e3 {In this lesson we
continue with White's main move 6.e3.} b6 {I am suggesting this move, which,
in my opinion, is a bit simpler than 6...c5 and 6...Nbd7. Black seems to
equalise without too much trouble - 6...b6 is just very solid! The big
theoretical lines are} (6... c5) ({and} 6... Nbd7) 7. cxd5 {In this lesson, we
check all the options apart from 7.Bd3, which is dealt with in Lesson 13.} (7.
Qc2 Ba6 {Putting pressure on c4 is best.} ({I don't like} 7... Bb7 8. cxd5 exd5
$14 {- White is better in this pawn structure.}) 8. Ne5 ({After} 8. cxd5 Nxd5 {
is best.} (8... Bxf1 {is inferior due to} 9. Kxf1 Nxd5 10. h4 $14) 9. Rd1 (9.
Bxa6 Nxa6 10. Nxd5 Qxd5 11. O-O c5 $11) ({After} 9. h4 Nxf4 10. exf4 {we don't
take on f1 (see 8...Bxf1), but play} Bb7 {with good counterchances.} 11. O-O-O
(11. Ng5 g6 12. O-O-O Bd6 $132) 11... Bxf3 12. gxf3 Nc6 13. Qe4 Nb4 14. f5 (14.
h5 Nd5 15. Bd3 Nf6 16. Qe3 Qd7 $132) 14... exf5 15. Qxf5 c6 16. Kb1 Qc8 17. Qe4
Re8 $132 {The position is double-edged but easier to play with Black due to
White's numerous weaknesses.}) (9. Qe4 c5 $132) 9... Nxf4 10. exf4 Bb7 $1 {
Better than} (10... Bxf1 11. Kxf1 {[%cal Gg2g3,Gf1g2] with a slightly passive
position for Black.}) 11. Ne5 Nc6 {The simplest.} (11... f6 $5 12. Nf3 Bxf3 13.
gxf3 Kh8 14. Bc4 Nc6 15. Qe4 Qd6 $13 {Both sides have weaknesses - the
position is unclear.}) 12. Bd3 g6 13. Be4 Nb4 14. Qb1 Nd5 $11) (8. O-O-O {
is playable but still a little risky.} Nc6 $5 {I like this best - the knight
is going to b4 or a5, creating counterplay.} (8... dxc4 9. h4 Nbd7 10. Ng5 b5
11. Nce4 g6 12. Be2 Bb7 $132) 9. a3 (9. h4 Nb4 10. Qb3 dxc4 11. Bxc4 b5 12. Be2
