14. Qxe8 Rfxe8 15. Ke2 Rac8 $11 {The pawn structure is symmetrical and Black
has no weaknesses.}) 11... Qe8 12. Qb3 (12. Qxe8 Rfxe8 13. Bxc7 Nd3 $44 {
gives Black at least enough compensation for the pawn.}) 12... Rc8 $11 {
[%cal Gc7c5]}) (10. O-O c5 11. Rc1 Nb4 12. dxc5 Bxc5 $11) (10. Qe2 Qc8 11. O-O
c5 12. Nb5 Rd8 13. a3 Qb7 $11 {This looks completely equal. Black's a6-knight
will eventually re-enter the game.}) 10... c5 {Black gets enough counterplay.
For example} 11. Qe2 (11. O-O cxd4 12. Nxd4 Bc5 13. Be3 (13. Ndb5 Nb4 14. Bd6
Bxd6 15. Nxd6 Qe7 16. e5 Nfd5 17. Nxd5 Nxd5 $11 {The knight on d6 is no big
deal. We can challenge the e5-pawn with ...f6, while our knight is very stable
on d5.}) 13... Nb4 14. a3 Bxd4 15. Bxd4 Nc6 16. Be3 Ne5 17. Qe2 Qd3 $11) 11...
Qc8 {The queen heads for b7 where it's ideally placed.} ({or} 11... cxd4 $5 12.
Rd1 Qc8 13. Nxd4 Rd8 $11) 12. O-O Qb7 13. Rfd1 Rad8 14. Rac1 (14. d5 exd5 15.
exd5 Rfe8 16. Qc4 Nb4 17. d6 Bf8 $132) 14... Rfe8 $11) 9... Bxc4 (9... Qc8 {
is another decent move.}) 10. Qxc4 c5 11. dxc5 (11. O-O {led to complete
equality in a high-level game.} cxd4 12. Nxd4 Qc8 13. Qxc8 Rxc8 14. Rac1 Nbd7
$11 {0-1 (44) Mamedyarov,S (2817)-Nakamura,H (2746)/Kolkata IND 2018/The Week
in Chess 1253 (44)}) 11... Bxc5 {Keeping the structure symmetrical is the most
solid way to play.} ({Black is also close to full equality after} 11... bxc5
12. O-O Qb6 13. Rfd1 Nbd7) 12. O-O (12. Rd1 Qc8 13. O-O Be7 $11 {doesn't
change much.}) (12. Rc1 Nbd7 13. O-O Qc8 {transposes to the main line.}) 12...
Qc8 {The queen is heading for b7 or in some cases a6.} 13. Rac1 (13. Rfd1 {
White can also start with} Nbd7 ({I am not fond of the endgame after} 13... Qa6
$6 14. Qxa6 Nxa6 15. a3 $14 {[%csl Ra6]}) 14. Qe2 (14. Ne5 Nxe5 15. Bxe5 Be7
16. Qe2 (16. Qa4 a6) 16... Qb7 17. Bd6 Bxd6 18. Rxd6 Rad8 $11 {1/2 (29)
Wojtaszek,R (2727)-Dominguez Perez,L (2732)/Huaian 2016/CBM 171 Extra (29)}) (
14. Ng5 $6 {was played by me against Dominguez. However, I failed to pose any
problems.} Be7 15. Qe2 Qb7 16. Rac1 Rac8 $11 {1/2 (71) Cheparinov,I (2687)
-Dominguez Perez,L (2723)/Varadero 2016/CBM 173 (71)}) 14... Rd8 $1 {The most
accurate!} 15. e4 (15. Rd2 Nf8 $11) (15. Rac1 Qb7 16. Na4 (16. Nb5 h6 $11)
16... Rac8 {Black can give the bishop since all of his remaining pieces will
be excellently placed.} 17. Nxc5 Nxc5 18. h3 Nd5 $11) 15... Nf8 16. Rxd8 Qxd8
17. Rd1 Qe8 $11) (13. Nb5 Nbd7 14. Rac1 Qa6 {Now, if the b5-knight moves,
Black can exchange queens leading to full equality.} 15. Rfd1 Rac8 16. Nd6 Qxc4
17. Nxc4 Nd5 $11) 13... Nbd7 {transposes to the main line.} ({Black is
slightly worse after} 13... Qb7 14. Nb5 $14) 14. Qe2 Qb7 15. e4 {White
advances in the centre. This continuation requires some precision on Black's
part.} Rfe8 $1 {[%csl Re2,Ge8][%cal Ye8e2,Ge4e5,Gf6d5] An important
prophylactic move! Black prepares to meet 16.e5 with 16...Nd5 and anticipates
the opening of the e-file.} 16. e5 (16. Rfd1 Nf8 {[%cal Gf8g6]} 17. Bg5 Ng4 18.
Bh4 Ng6 19. Bg3 Rad8 $11) ({After} 16. a3 {Black can go for} e5 {himself.} (
16... Nf8 17. e5 Ng6 {is a decent alternative.}) 17. Bg3 Rac8 18. Rfd1 Bd4 $5 (
18... Bf8 $11) 19. Nxd4 exd4 20. Rxd4 Nxe4 21. Re1 Nd6 22. Qd2 Rxe1+ 23. Qxe1
Re8 24. Qd2 Nf5 25. Rd3 Nxg3 26. hxg3 Nf6 $11) 16... Nd5 17. Nxd5 (17. Qe4 Rac8
$11) 17... exd5 $1 {The point of 15...Rfe8!} ({Black lands in an unpleasant
position after} 17... Qxd5 $6 18. Rfd1 Qb7 19. Ng5 Nf8 20. Ne4 $14) 18. Qb5 (
18. Qd2 Nf8 19. b4 Be7 $11 {[%cal Gf8e6]}) 18... Rec8 {I like this best. Next,
we bring our knight to e6.} (18... a6 19. Qb3 Rac8 20. Rcd1 d4 {probably
equalises too.}) 19. a3 (19. Rfd1 Nf8 20. Qd3 Ne6 $11) (19. Rcd1 Nf8 20. Qd3 d4
21. Nxd4 Bxd4 22. Qxd4 Ne6 23. Qe3 Rc2 $11 {Black has excellent compensation
for the pawn.}) (19. Nh4 {[%cal Gh4f5]} Nf8 20. Nf5 d4 21. Nd6 Bxd6 22. exd6
Qe4 23. Qe5 Qxe5 24. Bxe5 Rc5 $1 (24... d3 $5) 25. Bxd4 (25. Rxc5 $6 bxc5 $15 {
[%csl Gc5,Gd4]}) 25... Rd5 $11) 19... Nf8 20. b4 a6 21. Qd3 Be7 22. Be3 (22.
Nd4 {doesn't lead to anything.} Ne6 23. Be3 Nxd4 24. Bxd4 Rxc1 25. Rxc1 Rc8 $11
) 22... a5 (22... Ne6 {should be also fine.}) 23. Qb5 (23. b5 Ne6 $11) 23...
axb4 24. axb4 Ne6 25. Nd4 (25. h3 Rc4 $11) 25... Nxd4 26. Bxd4 Rc4 $5 (26... h5
$11) 27. Rxc4 dxc4 28. Qxc4 b5 {Black has enough activity to compensate for
the missing pawn. He keeps the balance after for example} 29. Qc3 (29. Qb3 Qc6
$44) 29... Rc8 30. Bc5 Bxc5 31. bxc5 Qe4 32. Rc1 b4 33. Qa1 h5 $11 *

