1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 {After having examined all the systems with 3.Nf3, we
will deal with 3.Nc3 in the remaining chapters. I think that 3.Nc3 is slightly
preferable over 3.Nf3 since White can go for the Exchange Variation after 3.
Nc3 Nf6 4.cxd5 in its best version - White retains the option of developing
the king's knight to e2.} Nf6 4. Bf4 {We begin by examining White's lesser
options on move four. The main moves 4.Bg5 and 4.cxd5 will be analysed in
detail in the following Lessons. 4.Nf3 was already analysed in the lines
beginning with 3.Nf3.} (4. g3 $6 {It's dubious to combine an early Nc3 with g3.
} c5 $1 {Black immediately hits in the centre.} 5. dxc5 (5. cxd5 cxd4 6. Qa4+
Bd7 7. Qxd4 exd5 {[%cal Gb8c6]} 8. Nf3 (8. Nxd5 $6 {leads to an advantage for
Black.} Qa5+ 9. Nc3 Nc6 10. Qd1 Rd8 $15) 8... Nc6 9. Qd3 Bg4 10. Bg2 d4 $132)
5... d4 {A promising pawn sacrifice.} (5... Bxc5 6. cxd5 exd5 7. Bg2 d4 8. Na4
Be7 9. Nf3 Nc6 10. O-O O-O $11 {is a solid alternative.}) 6. Na4 Nc6 7. Bg2 e5
$132 {[%csl Ra4,Gd4,Ge5]}) (4. Qc2 $6 {is another dubious move.} c5 $1 {
Again, the most principled and active reaction.} 5. e3 (5. cxd5 $6 cxd4) (5.
dxc5 $6 d4) 5... cxd4 6. exd4 dxc4 7. Nf3 Qc7 $5 (7... Nc6 8. Bxc4 Be7) 8. Qa4+
Bd7 9. Qxc4 Bc6 10. Ne5 a6 11. Be2 Bd6 12. Nxc6 Nxc6 $15 {Black is already
slightly better.}) (4. e3 Be7 {will transpose to other lessons.}) (4. Nf3 {
transposes to the lines with 3.Nf3.}) 4... c5 $1 {The most ambitious and
logical move.} (4... dxc4 {is another option; for example} 5. e3 c5) 5. Nf3 (5.
cxd5 Nxd5 ({or} 5... cxd4 $5 6. Qxd4 Nc6 {followed by taking on d5.}) 6. Nxd5
exd5 (6... Qxd5 7. dxc5 Qxd1+ 8. Rxd1 Bxc5 $11) 7. e3 Nc6 8. dxc5 Bxc5 9. Nf3
O-O 10. Bd3 Qa5+ 11. Nd2 Qb6 $132 {Black has an active game.}) (5. dxc5 {
looks a little risky.} d4 6. Nb5 Bxc5 7. a3 (7. Nc7+ $6 Qxc7 8. Bxc7 Bb4+ 9.
Qd2 Bxd2+ 10. Kxd2 O-O $15) 7... e5 $1 8. Bxe5 Nc6 9. Nc7+ Kf8 10. Bxf6 Qxc7
11. Bg5 a5 $36 {I am not sure if Black is better objectively but he has good
chances to take over.}) (5. e3 cxd4 6. exd4 Bb4 {leads to a good version of
the Nimzo-Indian with a weird bishop on f4.} (6... Be7 {is also possible.}) 7.
Nf3 O-O 8. Bd3 dxc4 9. Bxc4 a6 (9... b6 10. O-O Bb7 $11) 10. a3 (10. O-O b5 11.
Bd3 Bb7 $132) 10... Bd6 11. Bg5 b5 12. Ba2 Be7 13. O-O Bb7 14. Re1 Nbd7 $11 {
Black is already slightly more comfortable.}) 5... cxd4 6. Nxd4 Nbd7 $1 {
[%cal Ge6e5] Black threatens ...e5.} 7. Qa4 Bc5 8. Nb3 (8. cxd5 O-O 9. Nb3 (9.
dxe6 $2 Nb6 $19 {and White loses material.}) 9... Nxd5 10. Nxd5 exd5 11. e3 Re8
$11 {Black has a playable position - White is lagging with his kingside
development.}) 8... O-O (8... d4 $5 9. Nxc5 dxc3 {is also enough for equality.}
) 9. Nxc5 (9. cxd5 {transposes.}) 9... Nxc5 (9... e5 $5 {is also possible
according to the engine.}) 10. Qa3 b6 11. cxd5 (11. Rd1 Bb7 12. e3 Qe7 $11 {
White has the pair of bishops but has fallen behind in development.}) (11. e3
Bb7 {is similar.}) 11... Nxd5 (11... exd5 {is also possible, keeping ...d4 as
an option.} 12. Rd1 Bb7 13. e3 Ne6 14. Bg3 (14. Be5 Ng4 15. Bd4 Qg5 $132) 14...
d4 15. Nb5 Nh5 16. Nxd4 Qf6 $44 {Black has very good compensation for the pawn.
}) 12. Nxd5 Qxd5 {Black is better developed, which offsets White's pair of
bishops. Black easily equalises after} (12... exd5 {is again interesting. For
example} 13. e3 d4 $5 14. Rd1 Bb7 $132) 13. f3 {[%csl Ge4][%cal Ge2e4]} (13.
Rd1 Qf5) 13... Rd8 14. e4 Nd3+ 15. Qxd3 Qxd3 16. Bxd3 Rxd3 17. Kf2 f6 {[%cal
Ge6e5]} 18. e5 (18. Rhd1 Ba6 19. Rxd3 Bxd3 20. Rd1 Bb5 $11) 18... Bb7 19. Rhc1
Rd7 $11 *

