1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. Bg5 dxc4 $5 {This is an interesting,
comparatively less known alternative to 4...Be7.} (4... Be7 {will transpose to
Lessons 8 to 10 after} 5. e3 h6 6. Bh4 ({or} 6. Bxf6 Bxf6) 6... O-O 7. Nf3) 5.
e3 (5. e4 b5 {In my opinion, this is a promising continuation - similar to an
analogous line in the Vienna Variation.} (5... c5 $5) 6. Nxb5 (6. Nf3 a6 {
transposes to Lesson 3.}) (6. e5 h6 7. Bd2 (7. Qf3 hxg5 8. Qxa8 Nfd7 $132) 7...
Nfd7 8. Nxb5 Nc6 $132) 6... Bb4+ 7. Nc3 c5 {Black has sacrificed a pawn, but
has won some time.} 8. Nf3 (8. d5 exd5 9. exd5 O-O 10. Bxc4 h6 (10... Bxc3+ 11.
bxc3 Nbd7 $44 {[%cal Gd7b6,Gd7e5]}) 11. Bxf6 ({White already must be careful
after} 11. Bh4 $6 Qe8+ $1 12. Qe2 Ne4 $15) 11... Qxf6 12. Nge2 Nd7 13. O-O Ne5
$11) (8. dxc5 Qxd1+ {The endgame is quite easy for Black. 8...Qa5+ is also
possible.} (8... Qa5 $5 9. Bxf6 gxf6 10. Nf3 Ba6 11. Qd4 Rg8) 9. Rxd1 Ba6 10.
Nf3 O-O 11. Nd2 Nbd7 12. Bxc4 Bxc4 13. Nxc4 Rfc8 $44 {[%cal Gc8c5,Gf6e4]}) ({
After} 8. e5 {Black has the amazing resource} Qd5 $1 {, more or less
equalising by force.} 9. Bd2 (9. Qa4+ Qd7) 9... Bxc3 10. bxc3 Ne4 11. Qa4+ Qc6
12. Qxc6+ Nxc6 13. Bxc4 cxd4 14. cxd4 Nxd4 $11) 8... Nc6 9. d5 {Now, Black
equalises with simple moves.} (9. Qa4 Bd7 10. dxc5 h6 11. Bd2 Bxc5 12. Bxc4 Qb6
13. O-O Ng4 14. Be1 Nd4 $132 {Black has great counterplay.}) (9. a3 Bxc3+ 10.
bxc3 Qa5 $132) 9... exd5 10. exd5 Qxd5 11. Bxf6 Qe6+ 12. Be2 Qxf6 $11) (5. Bxf6
{Giving up the bishop like this looks weird to me.} Qxf6 6. e3 b5 $5 {I like
this aggressive move.} (6... Bb4 7. Bxc4 c5) (6... g6 7. Bxc4 Bg7) 7. Nxb5 Bb4+
8. Nc3 c5 9. Bxc4 Bb7 $44 {Black has excellent compensation for the pawn - his
bishops are very strong.}) (5. Nf3 a6 {transposes to Lesson 3.}) 5... a6 {
This is the most logical in my view. Black plays in the spirit of the Queen's
Gambit Accepted.} (5... c5) (5... Be7) 6. Bxc4 ({If White prevents ...b5 with} 
6. a4 {, then Black benefits from the weakening of the b4-square.} Be7 (6... c5
7. Bxc4 Nc6 {leads to the same thing.}) 7. Bxc4 c5 8. Nf3 Nc6 9. O-O cxd4 10.
exd4 O-O {A typical IQP position. White would very much prefer to have his
pawn on a3 instead of a4. Black has equal chances. For example} 11. Re1 (11.
Qd2 h6 $5 (11... Nb4 12. Ne5 b6 13. Rfe1 Ra7 $132 {is complicated and not
worse for Black.}) 12. Bxh6 {This is good enough only for a draw.} (12. Bh4 b6
$11) ({After} 12. Bf4 {Black can offer the exchange of bishops with} Bd6 {
, when the following sacrifice leads to a draw.} 13. Bxh6 {Otherwise Black
obtains a very comfortable position.} (13. Rfd1 Bxf4 14. Qxf4 Ne7 $11) (13.
Rad1 Bxf4 14. Qxf4 Ne7 $11) 13... gxh6 14. Qxh6 Ng4 (14... Re8) 15. Qh5 Nf6 16.
Qh6 $11) 12... gxh6 13. Qxh6 Re8 14. d5 (14. Qg5+ $6 Kh8 15. Bd3 Ng8 16. Qh5+
Kg7 $15) 14... exd5 15. Nxd5 Nxd5 (15... Be6 $11) 16. Bd3 Nf6 (16... f5 17. Bc4
Qd6 18. Bxd5+ Qxd5 19. Qg6+ $11) 17. Qg5+ Kf8 $11) 11... h6 12. Bh4 {Black has
no problems and has often more than one way to play the positione during the
next few moves.} (12. Be3 Bd7 13. Qd2 Qa5 $11) (12. Bf4 Bd6 $1 13. Bxd6 (13.
Be5 Bb4 14. h3 Nxe5 15. Nxe5 Bd7 $11) 13... Qxd6 14. d5 exd5 15. Nxd5 Nxd5 16.
Bxd5 (16. Qxd5 Qb4) 16... Qb4 $11) 12... Bd7 (12... Re8) 13. Qe2 (13. Qd2 Rc8 {
is similar.}) 13... Re8 (13... Rc8) (13... Nh5) 14. Rad1 Nd5 15. Bxe7 Ncxe7 16.
Ne5 Bc6 $11 {Black has a solid position with good long-term prospects.}) (6.
Bxf6 {Giving up the bishop without being provoked by ...h6 looks somewhat
weird and poses no problems.} Qxf6 7. Bxc4 c5 8. Nf3 cxd4 9. Nxd4 (9. exd4 b5
10. Bb3 Bb7 11. d5 Nd7 12. O-O Nc5 13. dxe6 fxe6 $11) 9... g6 10. Rc1 Bg7 11.
O-O O-O $11 {[%cal Gf6e7]}) 6... c5 7. Nf3 (7. dxc5 {leads to easy equality.}
Qxd1+ 8. Rxd1 Bxc5 9. Nf3 (9. Ne4 Bb4+ ({We do not fall for} 9... Nxe4 $4 10.
Rd8#) 10. Kf1 Nbd7 $11 11. Nd6+ $2 {does not work due to} Bxd6 12. Rxd6 Ne4 $19
) 9... Nbd7 10. O-O b5 11. Be2 Bb7 $11) (7. a4 {transposes to 6.a4.}) 7... b5 {
This position is still fresh, with only a couple of games by strong players.}
8. Bd3 (8. Be2 Bb7 9. Ne5 {White tries to be active, since Black is doing
great once he finishes his development.} (9. O-O Nbd7 $11) 9... cxd4 10. exd4
Be7 11. Bf3 (11. O-O Nc6 {Now, White can try} 12. Nxb5 axb5 13. Bxb5 {which
leads to a forced draw after} Qd5 14. Qb3 O-O 15. Bxf6 Qxb3 16. axb3 Bxf6 17.
Nxc6 (17. Bxc6 Bxe5) 17... Bxc6 18. Bxc6 Rxa1 19. Rxa1 Bxd4 $11) 11... Ra7 {
A typical defensive resource.} 12. O-O O-O {Black will equalise step by step
and can hope for a long-term advantage due to White's isolated d4-pawn.} 13.
Rc1 (13. Be3 Bxf3 14. Qxf3 Rc7 $11) 13... b4 14. Na4 (14. Bxb7 Rxb7 15. Qf3 Rc7
$11) 14... Bxf3 15. Qxf3 Nd5 16. Bxe7 Nxe7 $11) (8. Bb3 Bb7 9. O-O (9. Qe2 Be7
10. Rd1 Nbd7 $11) 9... Be7 10. Qe2 Nbd7 11. Rad1 ({or} 11. e4 b4) 11... O-O 12.
e4 b4 {The following complications are not unfavourable for Black:} 13. d5 bxc3
14. dxe6 fxe6 15. Bxe6+ Kh8 16. Bxf6 (16. e5 {Black has several interesting
options against this.} Bxf3 (16... Qe8 $5 17. exf6 Bxf6) (16... Ng8 $5) 17.
gxf3 Ng8 18. Bxe7 (18. Rxd7 $6 Qe8) 18... Nxe7 19. Bxd7 (19. Rxd7 $6 Qe8) 19...
Ng6 20. Kh1 Qg5 (20... Nf4 21. Qc2) 21. Rg1 Qxe5 22. Qxe5 Nxe5 23. bxc3 Nxf3
$11) 16... Bxf6 17. Rxd7 Qb6 18. bxc3 Bc8 19. Qc4 Bxd7 20. Bxd7 Ra7 21. Ba4 (
21. Be6 Bxc3 22. Ng5 Qb4 23. Nf7+ Kg8 $11) 21... Re7 $11) (8. Bxf6 {Here, this
makes some sense since Black should take with the pawn!} gxf6 $1 (8... Qxf6 $6
9. Bd3 c4 10. Be4 Ra7 11. Nd2 $14) 9. Bd3 (9. Bb3 Bb7 10. O-O (10. Qe2 Nd7)
10... Nd7 11. Qe2 (11. d5 Qe7) 11... Qe7 (11... f5 $5 12. e4 Qf6) 12. Rad1 Bg7
13. d5 O-O 14. e4 Rad8 $132 {A complicated position with good potential for
counterplay for Black. His bishops may become strong one day.}) 9... f5 10. O-O
(10. dxc5 Bb7) 10... Bb7 11. Qe2 Nd7 12. Rad1 b4 $5 ({Another intesting try is
} 12... Bg7 13. dxc5 O-O {with excellent compensation for the pawn.}) 13. Na4
Rg8 {This leads to forcing play:} 14. Nxc5 Bxc5 15. dxc5 Rxg2+ $1 16. Kxg2 Qg5+
17. Kh1 Qg4 18. e4 fxe4 19. Rg1 exd3 20. Rxd3 Qf5 21. Rg8+ Ke7 22. Rxa8 Bxa8
23. Kg1 Nxc5 24. Re3 Qg6+ 25. Kf1 Bc6 26. Nd4 Bg2+ 27. Ke1 Bd5 $44 {The
position is still very sharp yet dynamically equal.}) 8... Nbd7 $1 {An
important subtlety!} ({White has the initiative after} 8... Bb7 $6 9. Be4 $1
Bxe4 10. Nxe4) 9. Be4 {This is the critical line.} (9. a4 b4 10. Ne4 Bb7 11.
Nxf6+ Nxf6 12. dxc5 Bxc5 13. O-O O-O 14. Qe2 ({This wins a pawn, though it
does not lead to an advantage.} 14. Bxh7+ Kxh7 15. Qc2+ Kh8 16. Qxc5 Bxf3 17.
gxf3 {Black can force a drawish endgame with} Nd7 18. Bxd8 Nxc5 19. Be7 Rfc8
20. Bxc5 Rxc5 {[%cal Gc5c2]} 21. Rfc1 Rac8 $11 {Black has sufficient
counterplay for the missing pawn.}) 14... Be7 15. Rfd1 Qa5 16. e4 Rfd8 $11) (9.
O-O Bb7 $11) 9... Ra7 10. Rc1 (10. Bc6 Be7 11. dxc5 (11. Bxf6 gxf6 12. d5 Qc7
$132) 11... O-O 12. b4 Nb8 13. Qxd8 Bxd8 14. Nd4 e5 15. Ndxb5 axb5 16. Bxb5 Ra3
17. Nb1 Ra7 18. Nc3 {White needs to play for a repetition since he cannot play
18.a4.} (18. a4 $2 Nd5 $19) 18... Ra3 $11) (10. Ne5 $6 {is dubious and leads
to an advantage for Black.} Nxe5 11. dxe5 Qxd1+ 12. Rxd1 Nd7 13. f4 h6 14. Bh4
c4 $15 {[%csl Ga6,Gb5,Gc4]}) (10. O-O Be7 11. dxc5 (11. Qc2 {Here we can go for
} c4 12. Rfd1 h6 $132 {with a very playable position.}) 11... Nxc5 12. Qxd8+
Bxd8 13. Bc6+ (13. Ne5 O-O 14. Nc6 Rd7 $11) 13... Bd7 14. Ne5 Bxc6 15. Nxc6 Rc7
16. Nxd8 Kxd8 17. Rac1 Nd3 18. Rfd1 Rd7 19. Rc2 Ke7 20. Ne4 Rhd8 $11) 10... h6
11. Bxf6 (11. Bh4 $2 g5 {loses some material since after the bishop moves ...
b4 is coming.}) 11... Nxf6 12. Bc6+ (12. Ne5 Rc7) 12... Bd7 13. Ne5 Rc7 14.
Nxd7 Nxd7 15. d5 exd5 16. Qxd5 {The only way to pose problems.} (16. Bxd5 c4
17. O-O (17. Qf3 Qf6 $132) (17. Bxf7+ $6 {looks dangerous but does not work.
After} Kxf7 18. Qd5+ Ke8 19. Qh5+ Ke7 20. Nd5+ Kd6 21. Rd1 Kc6 $17 {Black's
king escapes.}) 17... Bb4 $11) 16... Be7 17. Bb7 ({Black has no problems
equalising after} 17. O-O O-O 18. Rfd1 Nf6 19. Qxd8 Rxd8 20. Rxd8+ Bxd8 $11) (
17. Ke2 {does not change much.} O-O 18. Rhd1 Nb6 19. Qh5 Qc8 $11) 17... b4 $1
18. Na4 (18. Ne4 a5 19. Nd2 O-O 20. Nc4 {The knight looks beautiful on c4 but
Black will soon exchange it.} Qb8 21. Bc6 Nb6 22. Nxb6 Qxb6 $11) 18... O-O 19.
b3 ({If White takes the pawn} 19. Bxa6 {, then Black can force a draw with} Ra7
20. Bb5 Qa5 21. Bxd7 Rd8 22. b3 Raxd7 23. Qc6 Rd6 24. Qb7 (24. Qf3 c4 $1) 24...
R6d7 $11) 19... Nf6 {Black can go for the endgame. Even if he will be down a
pawn, he will have no trouble in holding the position due to his active pieces.
} 20. Qxd8 Rxd8 21. Bf3 (21. Bxa6 Rcd7 22. O-O Rd2 23. Nxc5 Rxa2 24. Bb7 g6 25.
Bf3 Ra3 $11) 21... c4 22. bxc4 Rd3 23. Bd1 Ne4 24. Bc2 Ra3 25. Bxe4 Rxa4 26.
