1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. cxd5 {The final three lessons of this course
are dedicated to the ever popular Exchange Variation. We begin by examining
White's lesser alternatives on move five.} exd5 5. Bf4 (5. Qc2 $6 {is not a
great move.} Nc6 $5 {already forces a concession since} (5... c5 6. e3 Nc6 {
is also good.}) 6. Nf3 $2 Nb4 $1 $17 {[%cal Gc8f5] is bad for White.}) (5. g3
$6 Bd6 6. Bg2 O-O 7. Nf3 c6 8. O-O Re8 $15 {Next, Black's light-squared bishop
comes to f5. Black is already better since White's bishop is misplaced on g2.})
(5. e3 Bd6 6. Bd3 O-O 7. Nge2 Re8 8. O-O c6 $132 {is similar to a line of the
Nimzo-Indian. Here, Black's bishop is already placed perfectly on d6.} (8... b6
$132 {[%cal Gc7c5]})) 5... c5 {Black has several options, but I like 5...c5,
attacking the centre.} (5... Bd6 6. Bxd6 Qxd6 7. e3 Bf5 $11 {is completely
fine too.}) 6. Nf3 (6. e3 Nc6 7. Bb5 (7. Nf3 {transposes to 6.Nf3.}) (7. dxc5
Bxc5 8. Nf3 O-O 9. Be2 d4 $11) 7... cxd4 8. exd4 (8. Qxd4 Be7 9. Nge2 (9. Qa4
Qb6) 9... O-O 10. Qa4 Qb6 11. O-O Rd8 12. Rfd1 Be6 $11) 8... Bd6 9. Nge2 O-O
10. O-O Bf5 $11) 6... Nc6 7. g3 {We get a position similar to the Tarrasch
Defence with a strangely placed white bishop on f4.} ({After} 7. e3 {Black can
go for} c4 $1 8. a3 (8. Be2 Bb4 9. O-O O-O $132 {Black has good control over
e4.}) 8... Be6 9. Ng5 (9. Be2 Be7 10. O-O O-O 11. Ne5 Rc8 $11 {I think this
structure is very good for Black. It's difficult for White to achieve e4.})
9... Bd6 10. Nxe6 fxe6 11. Bxd6 Qxd6 12. b3 cxb3 13. Qxb3 O-O 14. Be2 Rfc8 $11
{Black has no problems.}) 7... Bg4 (7... cxd4 {is another logical way to play.}
8. Nxd4 Bc5 9. Nb3 Bb4 10. Bg2 O-O 11. O-O Bxc3 12. bxc3 Re8 $11) (7... c4 {
is possible too, leading to double-edged play after} 8. Bg2 Bb4 9. O-O O-O $13)
8. Be3 c4 (8... Bxf3 9. exf3 cxd4 10. Bxd4 {is probably a little bit better
for White.}) 9. Bg2 Bb4 10. O-O h6 11. Ne5 Bf5 12. Qa4 Bxc3 13. bxc3 O-O 14.
Qb5 (14. Nxc6 Qd7) 14... Qc8 $1 {Black protects everything and has a good
position. It's important that our strong bishop on f5 controls b1. Winning the
pawn on d5 gives Black fully sufficient compensation after} 15. Bxd5 a6 16.
Qxc4 Nxe5 17. dxe5 Nxd5 18. Qxd5 Qxc3 19. Qxb7 Qxe5 $44 {[%csl Gf5][%cal Gf5e4]
White has kept the extra pawn but his king is a bit weak. Black is not worse.}
*

