1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. cxd5 exd5 5. Bg5 c6 6. Qc2 {With this move,
White prevents the line 6.e3 Bf5 (which I am not recommending for Black,
though it's playable). We will examine the main move 6.e3 in Lesson 18.} h6 $1
{In my opinion, this is always useful.} 7. Bh4 (7. Bf4 {can be met with} Nh5 $1
8. Be5 ({After} 8. Bd2 {we can develop our bishop to an active position with}
Bd6) 8... Nd7 9. e3 Nxe5 (9... Nhf6 $11 {is possible, though it allows White
to repeat with} 10. Bg3 Nh5 11. Be5) 10. dxe5 g6 $132 {Black can even fight
for an advantage because he has gained the pair of bishops.}) (7. Bxf6 Qxf6 8.
e4 {Having given up the dark-squared bishop, White plays for activity. Black
has zero problems after} ({Black is at least equal after} 8. Nxd5 Qxd4 9. Rd1 (
9. Nc7+ $2 {does not work because after} Kd8 $19 10. Rd1 {is met with} Bb4+)
9... Bb4+ 10. Nxb4 Qxb4+ $11) (8. e3 Nd7 $132 (8... Bf5 $11)) ({After} 8. Nf3
$6 {White has no compensation for giving up the pair of bishops.} Bf5 $15) 8...
Qxd4 ({or} 8... dxe4 $5 9. O-O-O Be7 10. Nxe4 Qf5 $132) 9. Nf3 (9. Rd1 Qc5 10.
exd5 Be7 $11) 9... Qc5 10. exd5 Be7 11. Rd1 O-O $11) 7... g6 $5 {[%cal Gc8f5]
I think that this is a decent way to play - Black prepares ...Bf5.} ({Black
can also play the simple} 7... Be7 {transposing to Lesson 18 after either} 8.
e3 ({or} 8. Nf3 O-O 9. e3)) 8. e3 (8. f3 $6 {might look interesting but after}
Bg7 9. O-O-O O-O 10. e4 dxe4 11. fxe4 Qa5 {Black is doing great:} 12. Bc4 (12.
Kb1 Be6 $15) (12. Nf3 Be6) 12... Ng4 $15) 8... Bf5 9. Bd3 {I think that White
should exchange the bishops since otherwise the f5-bishop is very well placed.}
(9. Qb3 g5 10. Bg3 (10. Qxb7 $2 gxh4 11. Qxa8 Qb6 $17 {and White's queen will
be trapped.}) 10... Qb6 11. h4 Rg8 (11... g4 $5) 12. hxg5 hxg5 13. f3 Nbd7 $11)
(9. Qd2 Bg7 10. f3 O-O $11) 9... Bxd3 10. Qxd3 Nbd7 $1 {An important moment!
It's best to start with 10...Nbd7 in order to retain the option of ...Be7
after 11.f4.} ({White is better after} 10... Bg7 11. f4 $1 {[%cal Gg1f3]} O-O
12. Nf3 Nbd7 13. O-O $14) 11. Nge2 {This is White's best continuation,
planning 0-0, f3, Re1, and e4.} (11. Nf3 Bg7 12. O-O O-O $11 {Although the
bishop is in an unusual position on g7, Black's position is fine.}) ({The plan
with castling queenside is dubious:} 11. f3 Bg7 12. O-O-O $6 b5 $1 {Black gets
dangerous counterplay.} 13. e4 dxe4 14. fxe4 b4 15. Nce2 g5 16. Bg3 O-O 17. Bd6
Re8 18. e5 c5 $132) ({If now} 11. f4 {then Black plays} Be7 $1 12. Bxf6 (12.
Nf3 $6 {is already met with} Ne4 $1 $15) 12... Nxf6 13. Nf3 O-O 14. Ne5 Bd6 15.
O-O Kg7 $11) 11... Bg7 12. O-O (12. f3 O-O 13. Bf2 (13. O-O-O $2 b5 $1 $17)
13... Re8 14. O-O {transposes to the main lines.}) (12. O-O-O $2 b5 $1 $17 {
Black is faster with his attack.}) 12... O-O 13. f3 Re8 14. Rae1 (14. e4 {
leads to massive exchanges after} dxe4 15. fxe4 g5 16. Bg3 Nc5 17. Qf3 Ncxe4
18. Nxe4 Nxe4 ({We need to avoid} 18... Rxe4 $2 19. Be5 $16) 19. Qxf7+ Kh8 20.
Be5 (20. Qxb7 Nxg3 21. Nxg3 Qxd4+ 22. Kh1 Qxb2 $11) 20... Bxe5 21. dxe5 Qb6+
22. Kh1 Rf8 23. Qg6 Rxf1+ 24. Rxf1 Nf2+ 25. Rxf2 Qxf2 26. Qxh6+ $11) (14. Bf2
Nf8 ({or} 14... Nb6 15. b3 Qe7 $11) 15. Rad1 Qe7 $11 {[%cal Gf8e6,Ga8d8] The
position is balanced and playable for both sides.}) 14... Rc8 {[%cal Gc6c5]}
15. Qd2 (15. Bf2 Nf8 16. Nf4 (16. e4 dxe4 17. fxe4 c5 $132 (17... Ng4 $5) 18.
d5 $2 N8d7 $15) 16... Ne6 17. Nxe6 Rxe6 18. h3 Nh5 19. g4 Nf6 20. Kg2 Qd7 $11 {
1/2 (32) Yu,Y (2709)-Grischuk,A (2777) chess24.com INT 2020}) ({After} 15. Nc1
{Black creates counterplay with} b5 $1 16. Qd1 b4 17. Na4 c5 $11) 15... Bf8 $5
{This was played in a correspondence game.} (15... Nb6 {is also playable.} 16.
b3) 16. Bf2 Nb6 17. Qd3 (17. b3 a6 {[%cal Gc6c5] with the idea ...c5.}) 17...
c5 18. Rc1 cxd4 (18... a6 {is a decent move, keeping the tension.}) 19. Nxd4
Nc4 20. b3 Ne5 21. Qb1 Nc6 22. Nce2 Bb4 23. Rfd1 Qe7 $11 {1/2 (33) Gutkind,K 
(2239)-Ernst,C (2289) ICCF email 2021} *

