1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. cxd5 exd5 5. Bg5 c6 6. e3 {At last, we have
arrived of the main line of the Exchange Variation.} h6 {It's useful to
include this move - asking the bishop about his intentions.} (6... Bf5 {
is another big theoretical line, leading to the following endgame.} 7. Qf3 Bg6
8. Bxf6 Qxf6 9. Qxf6 gxf6) 7. Bh4 (7. Bf4 {is a decent alternative since
compared to 6.Qc2, Black doesn't have ...Nh5.} Bf5 {Now we can develop our
bishop without drawbacks.} 8. Nge2 (8. h3 Bd6 9. Bxd6 Qxd6 $11 {[%cal Gb8d7,
Ge8g8] Black has no problems - he will complete his development with ...0-0, ..
.Nbd7, ...Re8, etc.}) (8. Bd3 {also doesn't pose any problems.} Bxd3 9. Qxd3
Nbd7 10. h3 (10. Nge2 Nh5 {and Black exchanges White's bishop.}) 10... Be7 11.
Nf3 O-O 12. O-O Re8 $11 {Black has a decent position. Usually, when the
light-squared bishop are exchanged, Black is fine.}) 8... Nbd7 9. Ng3 Bh7 (9...
Be6 $5 {is an interesting alternative, setting a small trap.} 10. h4 ({White
loses material after} 10. Bd3 $2 g5 $1 11. Be5 Nxe5 12. dxe5 Ng4 $19) 10... Nb6
11. Bd3 Be7) 10. h4 Bb4 $1 {This is more active than ...Be7.} 11. Bd3 Bxd3 12.
Qxd3 O-O 13. a3 (13. f3 Re8 14. a3 Bf8 15. Kf2 g6 $15 {0-1 (46) Caruana,F 
(2804)-Dominguez Perez,L (2749) Saint Louis 2024. White is a little bit stuck
and Black has a good position.}) (13. Nf5 Nb6 14. a3 Bxc3+ 15. Qxc3 Qd7 16. Qc2
h5 {Preventing g4 once and for all. Black has a good position after} 17. f3
Rfe8 18. O-O Re6 $11 {, with counterplay along the e-file.}) 13... Bxc3+ 14.
bxc3 {The position is double-edged. Black has good counterplay on the light
squares. For example} Re8 15. h5 (15. Nf5 Nb6 16. g4 Nc4 $132) (15. f3 Nf8 16.
Nf5 Ng6 17. Bh2 Re6 18. g4 Ne7 $132) 15... a5 16. f3 (16. Nf5 b5) 16... b5 17.
O-O (17. Nf5 Nb6 18. g4 Nh7 19. Bxh6 gxh6 20. Nxh6+ Kg7 21. Nxf7 Qf6 $132)
17... Nf8 18. Qf5 (18. e4 Ne6 19. Qd2 Nd7 20. Nf5 Nb6 $11) (18. Rae1 Ne6 19.
Be5 Nd7 20. f4 f6 21. Bd6 Nb6 22. Bc5 Nc4 $132) 18... Ne6 19. e4 Nd7 20. Be3 (
20. Qg4 Nf6 $11) (20. exd5 cxd5) 20... Qh4 21. Kf2 Nb6 22. Rh1 Qe7 23. Qg4 Kh8
24. Nf5 Qf8 25. Rhe1 Nc4 $132 {These lines are quite complex, but Black enjoys
good counterchances and White also risks a lot playing like this.}) 7... Be7 8.
Bd3 {The most flexible move.} (8. Qc2 O-O 9. Nf3 (9. Bd3 {transposes to 8.Bd3.}
) 9... Ne4 {Black has zero problems after this move.} (9... Re8 10. Bd3 Ne4 {
is another possible move order.}) 10. Bxe7 (10. Nxe4 Bxh4 11. Nc3 Re8 $11)
10... Qxe7 11. Bd3 (11. Nxe4 dxe4 12. Ne5 (12. Nd2 Bf5 13. Be2 Nd7 $11) 12...
Nd7 13. Nxd7 Bxd7 $11) 11... Bf5 (11... Re8 12. O-O {Tr 8.Bd3.}) 12. Ne5 (12.
O-O Nd7 $11) 12... Re8 ({Even} 12... f6 $5 13. Nf3 Bh7 {, followed by ...Re8, .
..Nd7 is possible - the knight is very stable on e4.}) 13. O-O Nd7 14. f3 Nxe5
15. dxe5 Nxc3 16. Bxf5 Nb5 17. f4 f6 18. e6 (18. Bh7+ Kh8 19. Bg6 Rf8) (18. a4
Nc7 19. Bh7+ Kh8 20. Bg6 Rf8 21. Qc3 Kg8 22. b4 Rad8 $11 {1/2 (25) Pareschi,R 
(2107)-Romig,J (2141) FICGS email 2018}) 18... Nc7 19. Bh7+ Kh8 20. Bg6 {
This forces Black to sacrifice the exchange, but after} Qxe6 21. Bxe8 {1-0 (50)
