17. g4 Nxc3 18. bxc3 Qd8 {[%cal Gf7f6] Black is ready to chase away the knight
with ...f6. The following complications lead to equality:} 19. f5 f6 20. fxe6
fxe5 21. dxe5 Ne4 22. Bxe4 dxe4 23. Qf2 Qd5 24. Qf7+ Kh8 25. Qxb7 Qxe5 26. Qxc6
Rac8 27. Rf5 Qxh2+ 28. Kxh2 Rxc6 $11) (14. Rae1 Rc8 (14... Nfe4 $5 15. Bf4 Nxc3
16. Qxc3 Re8) 15. f4 Nfe4 $1 {A key resource in these lines - f4 can be met
with the pawn sacrifice ...Nfe4!} 16. Nxe4 dxe4 17. Bxe4 Nxe4 18. Qxe4 Bd5 19.
Qd3 f5 $44) (14. Rad1 Nde4 {If White takes the pawn on e4, then a2 is hanging
in the end.} (14... Nh5 $5) 15. Bh4 g5 16. Bg3 Nxg3 17. hxg3 {A doudle-edged
position in which Black also has chances for an advantage.} Bd6 18. e4 (18. f4
Ng4 $1 19. Qe2 h5 20. f5 (20. Qd2 gxf4 21. exf4 Qf6 22. f5 Bc8 $132) 20... Bxe5
21. dxe5 Bd7 22. Bb1 f6 23. e6 Qc7 24. Rf3 Be8 25. Rd4 Ne5 26. Rf1 Ng4 27. Rf3
(27. Qf3 Qe5 28. Nd1 Kg7 $132) 27... Ne5 $11) 18... dxe4 19. Bxe4 (19. Nxe4
Nxe4 20. Bxe4 Qf6 $11) 19... Qe7 20. f4 (20. Bf5 Bxf5 21. Qxf5 Qe6 22. Qf3 Rfe8
23. Rde1 Bf8 24. Re2 Rad8 25. Rd1 Kg7 $11) 20... gxf4 21. gxf4 Bxe5 22. dxe5 (
22. fxe5 Ng4) 22... Ng4 23. Rd3 Rad8 24. Rg3 f5 25. exf6 Qc5+ 26. Kh1 Rxf6 27.
Qe2 Qh5+ 28. Rh3 Nf2+ 29. Rxf2 Qxe2 30. Rxe2 (30. Nxe2 Bxh3 31. gxh3 Rd2 $132)
30... Bxh3 31. gxh3 Rxf4 32. Kg2 $11) (14. f3 Rc8 $1 {The thematic reaction
after f3 - Black prepares ...c5!} 15. Rad1 c5 $1 16. dxc5 Rxc5 17. Qe2 Re8 18.
Bb1 Rc8 $11) (14. Ne2 Qc8 15. Rae1 (15. Nf4 Bf5) (15. f3 Re8) 15... Re8 16. f3
Bf8 17. Kh1 (17. Bh4 c5) 17... Bf5 $11) ({Black's knight on d6 is perfectly
placed against the minority attack:} 14. b4 a5 15. a3 Nc4 $132) 14... Re8 15.
Bh2 (15. Rac1 Rc8 16. a3 (16. b4 $6 a5) 16... c5 17. dxc5 Rxc5 18. Nf3 Nfe4 19.
Be5 Qc8 20. Bd4 Rc6 21. Qd1 a6 22. Bc2 (22. Ne5 Rc7) 22... Rc7 $11) (15. a3 Qc8
16. Rac1 Bf5 17. f3 Bxd3 18. Nxd3 Qd8 $11) 15... Qc8 {A recurring idea -
preparing the exchange of light-squared bishops.} (15... Rc8 $6 16. Na4) 16. a4
Bf5 17. Bxf5 Nxf5 18. a5 (18. g4 Nd6 19. a5 a6 20. Na4 Bd8 21. Nxc6 Nde4 22.
Nb4 Qd7 23. Nd3 Nxg4 $11) 18... Bd6 19. a6 b6 20. Rfd1 (20. Qa4 c5) (20. Rac1
c5) 20... Ne7 $11 (20... Qe6)) (9. Nf3 Ne4 $1 10. Bxe7 Qxe7 11. Qc2 (11. O-O
Bf5) 11... Re8 {transposes to 8.Qc2 0-0 9.Nf3 Ne4.}) (9. h3 {With this move,
White plans to meet ...Re8 with Bg3.} Ne4 $5 (9... Re8) 10. Bxe7 Qxe7 11. Bxe4
(11. Qc2 Bf5 {is fine for Black.}) 11... dxe4 12. Nge2 (12. Qc2 {is similar to
12.Nge2.} f5 13. Nge2 Nd7 14. Qb3+ (14. Nf4 Kh7 15. h4 Nf6 16. h5 Re8 17. Nce2
Be6 $11 {[%csl Ge4,Gf5] Despite White managing to play h4-h5, Black is ok -
his structure is quite safe.}) 14... Kh7 15. O-O Nf6 16. d5 Nd7 $1 {[%csl Ge5]
[%cal Gd7e5] The knight is headed for the excellent e5-square. The position is
double-edged - some possible continuations:} 17. Rad1 (17. Nf4 g5 $1 18. Ne6
Rf7 $132) 17... Ne5 18. Nf4 (18. Rd2 Rb8 19. Rfd1 Bd7 $11) 18... g5 19. Nh5 Rb8
20. dxc6 (20. Qa4 a6) 20... Be6 21. Nd5 Bxd5 22. Qxd5 bxc6 23. Qd6 Qxd6 24.
Rxd6 Rxb2 $11) 12... f5 13. Nf4 Kh7 14. h4 Nd7 15. h5 Rd8 16. Qb3 Nf6 17. Nce2
b6 $11) (9. f3 {looks premature. After} Re8 10. Nge2 c5 $1 {[%cal Gb8c6] Black
can use same idea as after 8.f3.} 11. O-O Nc6 12. Rc1 (12. Qd2 c4 13. Bc2 Rb8 {
[%cal Gb7b5]} 14. Bg3 (14. a4 a6 15. a5 b5 16. axb6 Rxb6 17. Na4 Rb8 $11) 14...
Bd6 15. Bxd6 (15. Bh4 Be7 $11) 15... Qxd6 16. a4 a6 17. a5 b5 18. axb6 Rxb6 $11
)) 9... Ne8 $5 {[%csl Gd6][%cal Ye8d6] I prepared this modern way of playing
for this course. After either 9.Nge2 and 9.Qc2 we play 9...Ne8, transferring
the knight to d6.} (9... Re8) (9... Nbd7) 10. Bg3 (10. Bxe7 {As after 9.Qc2
Ne8, Black's position is very safe after the exchange of bishops.} Qxe7 11. O-O
Nd6 12. b4 (12. Ng3 Nd7 13. Qd2 Qg5 $1 {A strong move, creating counterplay.}
14. f3 (14. Rae1 h5 $1 15. f4 Qh6 16. e4 h4 $132) 14... h5 15. Rfe1 Nf6 $11) (
12. Qc2 Nd7 {leads to the same positions.}) 12... Bf5 13. Bxf5 (13. b5 Bxd3 14.
Qxd3 Nd7 15. bxc6 bxc6 16. Na4 Nb6 17. Nc5 Nbc4 $11 {Against the minority
attack, Black always can put a knight on c4.}) 13... Nxf5 14. b5 (14. Qc2 Nd6)
14... Nd7 15. bxc6 bxc6 16. Na4 (16. Qc2 Nd6 17. Na4 Nc4 $11) 16... Nd6 17. Rc1
Nc4 $11 {The strong knight on c4 shields the weak c6-pawn from an attack on
the c-file.}) 10... Nd6 11. Qc2 (11. O-O Re8 {leads to the same positions.})
11... Re8 12. O-O (12. h3 Bf8 13. O-O {is another transposition.}) 12... Bf8 {
This is Black's basic setup - he prevents the plan with f3 and e4 and will
often continue with ...a5, ...Na6-Nc7. Creating play on the queenside with ...
b5, ...b4, and possibly ...Ba6 can also be played in some lines.} 13. Rae1 {
The most logical move in my view - White prepares Nf4, f3.} (13. Rad1 a5 14.
Rfe1 (14. a3 Nd7 15. h3 Nf6 16. Be5 {1/2-1/2 (30) Nisipeanu,L (2615)-Moussard,
J (2686) Germany 2022} {Now Black could play} b5 $11 {with the idea of ...a5, .
..Ba6, ...b4 - another typical plan.}) 14... Na6 15. a3 Bd7 (15... Nc7) 16. Nc1
(16. h3 Nc7) 16... b5 17. e4 b4 18. Bxd6 Bxd6 19. e5 Bf8 (19... bxc3 20. exd6
cxb2 21. Qxb2 Be6 $11) 20. Na4 bxa3 21. bxa3 {½- (124) ½ (124) Rodshtein,M 
(2604)-Lupulescu,C (2573) Chartres 2023} Bxa3 22. Bxa6 Bxc1 23. Rxc1 Rxa6 $11)
(13. Kh1 a5 14. a3 (14. Rae1 b5) (14. Ng1 {Against this slow move, Black can
exchange the light-squared bishops with} b6 15. Nf3 Ba6 16. Ne5 Bxd3 17. Qxd3
a4 18. Rfc1 a3 19. b3 Qe7 20. f3 Rc8 $11) {Here we go for} 14... Nd7 {,
followed by ...Nf6. ½-½ (65) Salem,A (2633)-Sargissian,G (2559) Almaty 2022}
({It's not easy to understand, but according to the engine, White is slightly
better after} 14... Na6 15. Ng1 $1 Nc7 16. Nf3 Be6 $14) 15. h3 (15. Ng1 Nf6)
15... Nf6 $11) (13. Nf4 a5 $1 14. Rfe1 {Again, preparing f3 - this time with
the king's rook.} (14. Rad1 b5 $5 {Here, I like this best.} (14... Na6 15. a3
Nc7 {is also fully playable.}) 15. h3 (15. Rfe1 Na6 16. Qb1 Bd7 $132) 15... Nd7
16. e4 (16. Rfe1 Nf6) 16... b4 17. e5 bxc3 18. exd6 cxb2 19. Qxc6 Rb8 20. Nxd5
Bb7 21. Ne7+ Bxe7 22. dxe7 Bxc6 23. exd8=Q Rbxd8 24. Rd2 (24. Rb1 Be4) 24...
Nf6 25. Rxb2 Rxd4 26. Ba6 Ne4 $11) (14. a3 Na6 15. Rfe1 {leads to 14.Rfe1.}) (
14. Rae1 {transposes.}) 14... Na6 (14... b5 15. a3) 15. a3 Nc7 (15... b5 16. f3
Nc7 17. e4 dxe4 18. fxe4 Nc4 19. Nfe2 Ne6 20. Bf2 $14) 16. Na4 (16. Rad1 Ne6
17. h3 (17. f3 Nxf4 18. Bxf4 b5 19. b3 (19. e4 b4 20. e5 Nc4 21. axb4 axb4 22.
Na4 Rxa4 $1 {Black equalises using tactics.} 23. Bxc4 b3 $1 24. Bxb3 Rb4 25.
Be3 Qb6 26. Ba4 Rc4 27. Qb3 Rb4 $11) 19... Bd7 $11) 17... Nxf4 18. Bxf4 Qf6 $5
19. Be5 Qd8 20. Re2 Be6 $11) (16. e4 $2 {Playing this without a preliminary f3
is rarely good.} dxe4 17. Nxe4 Nf5 $1 $15) (16. f3 Ne6 17. Nxe6 Bxe6 18. Na4 (
18. e4 Nc4 {Creating counterplay in time with ...b5 coming next.} 19. Bf2 (19.
exd5 cxd5 20. Bxc4 dxc4 21. d5 Bd7 $11) (19. Bxc4 dxc4 20. Red1 Qb6 $5 21. Na4
Qb5 $11) 19... b5 $1 {Black gets fantastic compensation after} 20. exd5 cxd5
21. Nxb5 Rc8 22. Nc3 Bd6 23. Rac1 Qg5 $44) (18. Bf2 Nc4 19. a4 {White prevents
...b5, but now Black can use the b4-square after} Rc8 20. e4 dxe4 21. fxe4 Bb4
$11) 18... b5 {We can invite the knight to c5 since our knight will come to c4.
} 19. Nc5 a4 20. Nxe6 Rxe6 21. Bf2 (21. e4 Nc4) 21... Nc4 22. e4 Rc8 23. e5 {
It looks like White is better but Black gets sufficient counterplay with the
following exchange sacrifice.} (23. Rad1 c5) 23... c5 $1 24. Bf5 cxd4 25. Bxe6
fxe6 26. Qg6 (26. Bxd4 Nxa3 27. Qg6 Nc2 28. Qxe6+ Kh8 29. Rac1 Rc4 30. Bb6 Bc5+
31. Bxc5 Nxe1 32. Rxe1 Rxc5 $132) 26... Qb6 27. Kh1 Bc5 28. Re2 Rf8 29. Qd3 Rf5
30. Rae1 Ne3 31. h3 Rxe5 32. g4 Qd8 $1 33. Bg3 Qf6 34. Kg1 (34. Bxe5 Qxe5 35.
Qxb5 Qg3 36. Qxc5 Qxh3+ 37. Kg1 Qg3+ $11) 34... Rg5 35. f4 Rg6 36. Rc1 Nc4 $11)
(16. h3 Ne6 17. Nxe6 Bxe6 18. Rac1 Nc4 $11 (18... Qg5)) 16... Ne6 17. Nxe6 Bxe6
18. Nc5 (18. Rac1 {Here, we can go for the interesting.} Ne4 $5 19. Bxe4 (19.
Bf4 {If White saves the bishop, we play} b5 20. f3 Nd6 21. Nc5 a4 (21... Nc4
22. a4) 22. Bxd6 Qxd6 23. Qf2 Qb8 $11) 19... dxe4 20. Nc5 Bc8 21. Bf4 Qd5 $11)
(18. f3 b5 $11 {[%cal Ga5a4,Gd6c4]}) 18... Bc8 19. Rad1 (19. Rac1 b6 20. Na4
Bd7 21. h3 Rc8 $11) 19... b6 20. Na4 Bd7 21. f3 Nb7 $5 {This weird move,
preparing ...b5 is given by the computer.} ({White is probably better after} 
21... b5 22. Nc5 Nc4 23. e4 $14) 22. e4 (22. Nc3 b5) 22... dxe4 23. fxe4 (23.
Bxe4 Nd6) 23... b5 24. Nc3 b4 25. Na4 (25. axb4 axb4 26. Ne2 c5 $132) 25... Bg4
(25... bxa3 26. bxa3 Bxa3 27. Rf1 Bg4 28. Rb1 Nd6 29. Kh1 $13) 26. Be2 Bxe2 27.
Rxe2 bxa3 28. bxa3 Nd6 (28... Bxa3 29. Qxc6) 29. Bf2 Rc8 30. Nc5 Nb5 31. Rd3
Bxc5 32. Qxc5 Qd6 33. Qxd6 Nxd6 34. e5 Nf5 $11) (13. b4 Na6 $5 (13... Nd7 14.
b5 Nb6) 14. a3 (14. Rfb1 Nc4 15. a3 Nc7 16. e4 Be6 $11) 14... Nc7 15. Na4 (15.
a4 a5 16. b5 Bd7 17. Qb3 Rc8 $11) 15... Ne6 (15... Ncb5 $5 16. Nc5 b6 17. Nb3
Bd7) 16. Nc5 Ng5 17. Rfc1 h5 $132) (13. h3 a5 {[%cal Gb8a6,Ga6c7,Gc7e6]} 14.
Rfe1 Na6 15. a3 Nc7 16. Rac1 Bd7 17. Nf4 Ne6 $11) (13. Rfe1 a5 {will probably
transpose.}) 13... a5 14. Nf4 (14. a3 Na6 (14... b5 $5) 15. Bf4 (15. Nf4 {
see 14.Nf4.}) 15... b5 16. Ng3 Nc4 17. e4 Be6 18. exd5 cxd5 $1 {This is an
improvement over} (18... Bxd5 $6 19. Rxe8 Qxe8 20. Nxd5 cxd5 {1/2-1/2 (27)
Mamedyarov,S (2747)-Moussard,J (2686) Germany 2022} 21. Bc1 $14) {Black gets
excellent compensation after} 19. Nxb5 Qb6 20. a4 Nb4 $11 {[%csl Gb4,Gc4]}) (
14. Nd1 Na6 15. a3 Bd7 16. f3 Rc8 17. Nec3 c5 $132 {0-1 (37) Salem,A (2677)
-Carlsen,M (2859) Chess.com INT 2022}) 14... Na6 15. a3 Nc7 ({Carlsen played} 
15... Qf6 $6 {, but the queen turned out to be misplaced on f6.} 16. f3 b5 {
1/2-1/2 (39) Maghsoodloo,P (2721)-Carlsen,M (2856) Mayrhofen 2022} 17. Qf2 $14)
(15... Bd7 $5) 16. f3 (16. Na4 Ne6 17. Nxe6 Bxe6 18. Nc5 Bc8 $11) 16... b5 (
16... Nc4 17. e4 b5 {is similar.}) 17. b3 (17. e4 b4 18. axb4 axb4 19. Nce2 b3
$1 {An important tactical resource} 20. Qxc6 ({e4 is hanging after} 20. Qxb3
dxe4) 20... dxe4 21. fxe4 Bd7 22. Qc3 Nxe4 23. Bxe4 Rxe4 24. Qxb3 Bc6 $44) (17.
Bf2 Nc4 18. e4 b4 (18... Ba6 $5) 19. axb4 axb4 20. Nce2 (20. Nd1 {1/2 (31)
Maghsoodloo,P (2656)-Ter Sahakyan,S (2531) Almaty 2022} Ba6 $132) 20... b3 $1 {
Again, this resource which gives Black good activity after} 21. Qc1 Ba6 22. Rd1
Ne6 (22... Bb4 $5) 23. Nxe6 fxe6 24. Nf4 Qa5 $132) 17... Ne6 (17... a4 $6 18.
b4 Nc4 19. Qc1 $14) 18. Nxe6 Bxe6 19. Kh1 (19. e4 dxe4 20. fxe4 b4 21. axb4
axb4 22. Ne2 Ra3 $132) 19... Rc8 20. Ne2 (20. a4 c5 21. axb5 cxd4 22. exd4 Qb6
23. Qd2 Nf5 24. Bxf5 Bxf5 $44) 20... Qd7 {Black keeps the tension with a solid
and flexible position.} (20... Nb7 $5 {is another weird yet interesting way to
play.} 21. Nf4 Bd7) ({or} 20... a4 21. b4 (21. bxa4 Nc4 $132) 21... Nc4 22.
Bxc4 bxc4 23. Bf2 Qd7 24. e4 f6 $132) 21. e4 {The most straightforward
continuation. Black can counter White's play in the center by playing on the
light squares:} (21. Nf4 Bf5 $5 {Provoking e4, with the following piece
sacrifice in mind:} 22. e4 dxe4 23. fxe4 Nxe4 $1 {This is the point. The
complications will ultimately lead to simplifications and a draw.} 24. Bxe4 (
24. Rxe4 Bxe4 25. Bxe4 Qxd4 26. Bh7+ Kh8 27. Bf5 Rcd8 28. Qxc6 Qd1 29. Rg1 Qxb3
$132) 24... Rxe4 $1 25. Rxe4 Re8 26. Rfe1 Rxe4 27. Rxe4 Bxa3 {Black has two
pawns for the piece, while the pin is unpleasant. The line could continue with}
28. Ne2 Bf8 29. Nc3 b4 30. Nb1 a4 31. bxa4 b3 32. Qe2 Bxe4 33. Qxe4 Qa7 34. Nc3
Bb4 35. Qe8+ Kh7 36. Qe4+ Kg8 $11) 21... dxe4 22. fxe4 a4 23. b4 (23. bxa4 bxa4
24. Qxa4 Ra8 25. Qc2 Rxa3 26. Nf4 Bb3 27. Qb2 Rea8 $11) 23... Bc4 {White
managed to occupy the centre but with a great outpost on c4, Black can keep
the balance.} 24. e5 Bxd3 25. Qxd3 Nc4 26. Nf4 Be7 $1 27. e6 (27. h3 Bg5 28.
Nh5 Qe6 $132) 27... fxe6 28. Nh5 (28. Nxe6 Bxb4 29. Nxg7 Qxg7 30. axb4 Qh7 31.
Qd1 Qg6 $132) 28... Rf8 29. Qg6 Bg5 30. h4 Bd2 31. Rxf8+ Rxf8 32. Rxe6 Kh8 $1
33. Qe4 (33. Be5 Nxe5 34. dxe5 Be3 35. Kh2 c5 $132) 33... Qf7 34. Nxg7 Qxg7 35.
